<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe, United States Vie for Senior EBRD Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Europeans and the United States
are engaged in a fierce power struggle at the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) over the successor to the
outgoing EBRD first vice-president Ron Freeman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government, whose 10 percent stake makes it the bank's
largest single shareholder, is pressing hard for Freeman to be
replaced by another Wall Street banker, according to a report in
today's Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
However, European shareholders of the EBRD are fighting to
preserve the predominantly "European" character of the bank and
are determined to choose a European banker to replace Freeman, a
57-year-old Wall Street banker.
</P>
<P>
The major European investment bank, which was established in
1991 to facilitate the transition of eastern European countries to
market economies, concentrates its banking activity on the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
Freeman was chosen as one of two vice-presidents in charge of
the investment banking activities and Italy's Mario Sarcinelli was
put in charge of the development of banking operations.
</P>
<P>
But this division of functions was abolished in 1993 when
Sarcinelli was forced to resign after strong criticism over his
lavish refurbishment of the bank's London premises and Freeman
subsequently combined both operations, strengthening the American
position in the bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank is expected to present the names of suggested
candidates for Freeman's job at an informal board meeting Tuesday
and a final decision is likely to be made before the EBRD annual
meeting to be held in London Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
