<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hanbo Owner Gives Contradictory Testimony in Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The founder and owner of South
Korea's dissolved Hanbo Group gave contradictory testimony on
Monday while answering questions from lawmakers over the
bribes-for-loans scandal.
</P>
<P>
Chung Tae-soo, in the televised hearing and under tight
grilling in the Seoul Prison, acknowledged in the morning session
that he had "contributed to the election fund".
</P>
<P>
Asked about the size of the donation, he said: "A political
donation is limited to a maximum of one billion won (about 1.12
million U.S. dollars)."
</P>
<P>
But Chung reneged on his words in the afternoon after parties
involved rushed to release statements denying what Chung had said.
</P>
<P>
Chung also denied widespread allegations that President Kim
Young-sam's second son, Kim Hyun-chul, was involved in one of
South Korea's worst scandals.
</P>
<P>
Monday's hearing, the first of a series that will last for 25
days, focused on whether Chung had provided funds for Kim
Yong-sam's election campaign, which politicians had received money
from the Hanbo Group in exchange for preferential loans to the
group, and whether Kim Hyun-chul was involved in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
Asked key questions about the scandal, Chung simply said: "I
cannot answer because I am on trial," or "I do not remember."
</P>
<P>
The former corporate magnate also faces charges of embezzlement
and tax evasion. He was also indicted for bribing politicians and
government officials to obtain illegal loans without collateral.
</P>
<P>
From Monday until May 1, the National Assembly (parliament)
will hear testimony from 42 witnesses, including Chung, former
presidential advisors, and the president's son and his friends.
</P>
<P>
The Hanbo scandal flared up after the Hanbo steel firm, Hanbo's
flagship, collapsed with debts of 5.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The group was believed to have offered millions of dollars to
the then ruling party presidential candidate, Kim Young-sam, in
1992 presidential election campaigning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
