<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Sets Winter Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Winter Time started
from Sunday night when clocks were set back one hour, reported
the South African Press Association today.
</P>
<P>
Winter time in introduced, as usual, in Namibia on the first
Sunday of April each year when Standard Time is set to one hour
ahead of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT).
</P>
<P>
The period ends on the first Sunday in September when standard
time reverts to two hours ahead of GMT.
</P>
<P>
The time change, introduced to prevent children from having to
go to school in the dark, has prompted complaints from the
business community who say they lose four trading hours a day
with South Africa, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, trade unions are reportedly concerned with the
safety of female employees going home in the dark, while some
sportsmen and women have to train in the dark when no floodlights
are available, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
