<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Software Giant Plans Blending of Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Corporation, the
world's largest software company based in Redmond, Washington
state, is planning to blend the personal computer, the television
and the Internet by acquiring WebTV networks.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made Sunday from a convention of
telebroadcasters in Las Vegas, Nevada state, according to a report
of the New York Times today. Microsoft will send 425 million U.S.
dollars to acquire WebTV networks, a start-up company that
delivers Internet information directly to television.
</P>
<P>
The action is said to be Microsoft's most ambitious effort yet
to extend its reach from the personal computer, which has found
its way into almost 40 percent of American homes, to the
television, which has made entry into 98 percent of all homes in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
It is also described as a "milestone" in the challenge to the
world's television manufacturers by the computer industry, which
hopes to take over a substantial part of the new 150 billion U.S.
dollar market for digital television over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
The plan made to the public just a few days after the Federal
Communications Commission has set a nine-year timetable for the
nation's transition from analog to digital television. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
