<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing to Boost Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Co. is preparing to
increase its rate of production for all planes by 10 percent
beyond the record levels already announced, the Wall Street
Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
The company is studying how to double its current output rate
for the 737 aircraft, it said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Boeing said it plans to produce jetliners at a
record rate of 40 a month by the end of 1997, including 21 of the
737s, the popular line of planes in the 150- to 170-seat range.
Boeing's previous record production rate for all models was 39.5
planes a month, reached in mid-1992.
</P>
<P>
The world's largest plane maker has already decided to boost
production by at least 10 percent overall. That will include
turning up production of the 737 to 24 planes a month or more in
the next two years, and increasing production of its 747 jumbo
jets by 25 percent, to five planes a month from four. Boeing has
already said it is increasing production of its 300-seat 777 by 40
percent, to seven planes monthly, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Boeing also plans to produce the 737 at rates of 28 to 31
planes a month in 1999 and 2000. At the moment, it is in the
process of increasing production of that plane to 17 by this fall.
</P>
<P>
The paper said such a move would boost overall production rates
for all models to as many as 48 planes monthly by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
By mid-1999, Boeing expects to be making only its three sizes
of "737-X" upgraded versions of the plane, and will have ceased
making three less-efficient "classic" versions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
