<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tide Causes Lobster Walk-Out in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- About 500 to 1,000 tons of
rock lobsters have "walked out" of the sea onto the beaches at
Elands Bay in Western Cape Province at the weekend to escape
toxic red tide which depletes oxygen levels in the waters.
</P>
<P>
The South African Press Association reported that Hordes of
visitors streamed to the picturesque Cape West Coast beaches
today and on Sunday to collect the delicacy, using black refuse
bags, empty milk carton containers and laundry baskets.
</P>
<P>
The walk-out was the second time in the past two weeks that
huge numbers of crayfish crawled from the sea. About 60 tons of
rock lobsters emerged from the ocean at Elands Bay shortly before
Easter.
</P>
<P>
The Easter rock lobster walk-out was dominated by non-toxic
organisms and the rock lobsters were probably affected by a lack
of oxygen in the water.
</P>
<P>
The latest crayfish walk-out is thought by locals to be the
largest ever in the history of the town.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, scientists were reportedly on their way to the area
to ascertain whether red tide was responsible for the walk-out.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities are collecting as many crayfish as possible and
placing them in holding tanks before being relocated to the sea in
other areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
