<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Patch-up Chances Between Congress, United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- With both the Congress Party and
the United Front (UF) refusing to climb down from their stand,
chances of reaching a compromise before the April 11 vote of
confidence have receded.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Deve Gowda is getting ready for a nationally
televised debate in the Lower House of Parliament on April 11, the
date set by President S.D. Sharma for the UF government to show
its majority in parliament through a vote of confidence following
the withdrawal of support to it by the Congress on March 30. And
he has refused to make way for another candidate to lead the UF
before the trial of strength this Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, leaders of both the Congress and the UF
have had a series of informal contacts trying to solve their
disputes, yet both of them have adhered to their own stand. While
the Congress put the change of the leadership in the UF government
as a precondition for further talks, the UF insisted that the
Congress should reconsider its withdrawal of support. They said
that they could listen to the grievances of the Congress, but they
refused to change the leadership of the UF government.
</P>
<P>
It appears that any realignment among the secular parties, if
at all to be arrived at, will be possible only after the vote of
confidence as Gowda has tremendous faith in his "destiny." The
prime minister is busy with his 40-page speech, to be delivered on
the floor of Parliament, listing achievements and giving
blow-by-blow account of how the corrupt Congress was trying to
browbeat him.
</P>
<P>
Informal meetings are still going on between the Congress and
the UF in a bid to break the present impasse. Indian External
Affairs Minister I. K. Gujral has said that after meeting Congress
President Sitaram Kesri Sunday morning his talks were "positive."
UF Spokesman Jaipal Reddy appeared confident of finding a solution
by April 8 between the Congress and the UF.
</P>
<P>
Indian President S. D. Sharma, who met leaders of the UF and
the Congress in the past week, is learnt to have advised them to
find an amicable settlement to avoid a snap poll in the interest
of the country. Both the Congress and the UF are also reportedly
not in favor of mid-term elections.
</P>
<P>
Among the 543 seats in the Lower House of Parliament, the UF
has 188 seats including 11 supporters from the outside and the
Congress has 141 seats while the BJP alliance occupies 193 seats.
With the same purpose to prevent "communal force" of BJP from
coming into power, both the UF and the Congress came together as
"secular force" with the former coming to power on June 1 last
year with the support of the latter. Without the Congress support,
the UF government is expected to fall.  
</P>
</TEXT>
