<HEADLINE> Americas Cup Backs to Britain For Repairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The world oldest sporting trophy --
the Americas Cup -- has been brought back to Britain on Monday to
be repaired by the Crown jewellers who created it 146 year ago.
</P>
<P>
The greatest trophy in yachting, which was made in Britain in
1851 but has spent most of the past century in the United States,
was partially destroyed by a protester in March while it was on
display in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"The top third of the cup is very badly damaged. It's been
beaten around quite severely with a sledgehammer and so there is
quite of lot of restoration work to be done on that part of it,"
said John Heise, the commodore of the Royal New Zealand yachting
Squadron who accompanied the cup.
</P>
<P>
It was transported in a specially made case, on a first class
flight from Auckland.
</P>
<P>
Jewellers Garrards estimate it will take up to eight weeks to
repair the silver cup.
</P>
<P>
Militant New Zealand Maori Benjamin Peri Nathan, 27, was
charged with wilfully destroying the cup on March 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
