<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, U.S. Agree to maintain U.S. Troop Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Defense Agency chief Fumio
Kyuma and United States Defense Secretary William Cohen today
agreed to maintain the present level of U.S. troops in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Kyodo News Service quoted Defense Agency officials as
saying the two defense chiefs reached the agreement in talks
tonight in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Japan hosts 47,000 of the 100,000 U.S. troops deployed in East
Asia. About 27,000 are stationed on Japan's island prefecture of
Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
The two men also agreed that the two countries would draw up an
interim report in May, reviewing the 1978 guidelines on
Japan-U.S. defense cooperation, agency officials said.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the two countries would continue a joint study
of the Theater Missile Defense System (TMD), a regional
anti-missile defense system Japan has been studying for about two
years to decide whether or not to participate in its development,
the officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived in Tokyo earlier today for a three-day visit to
Japan for talks with Japanese leaders on the U.S. military
presence in Okinawa, and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
