<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Kills 1.5 Million in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- About 3.1 million people were
infected with AIDS and another estimated 1.5 million died of
AIDS-related diseases last year, a report by a sub-institution of
the United Nations showed.
</P>
<P>
The deaths included 350,000 children, according to a report
released today by the Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS
(UNAIDS).
</P>
<P>
The death figure accounted for about 25 percent of all
AIDS-related mortality since the outbreak of the epidemic in the
early 1980s, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that despite signs of decreases in new infections and
deaths in several countries, new epidemics related with AIDS or
HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, are spreading at alarming rates
in Asia and in Central and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Peter Piot, executive director of the Program Coordinating
Board, the governing body of the UNAIDS, said there was a lack of
prevention strategies that are cost-effective and work.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed the continuing denial of AIDS (Acquired Immune
Deficiency Syndrome), in many societies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
