<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Taiwan, Hong Kong Industrialists (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xiamen, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Vice-premier Qian Qichen, in a
meeting with industrial and commercial leaders from Taiwan and
Hong Kong in Xiamen this evening, expressed the hope that the
Taiwan Authorities will no longer prevent entrepreneurs from
investing in the mainland, because it is not in the interest of
Taiwan compatriots.
</P>
<P>
Qian made a special trip to the southeast Chinese city earlier
this evening to attend the first commodity fair for Xiamen exports
to Taiwan and a travel and shopping festival for Taiwan
Compatriots which is scheduled to open Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Taiwan Authorities to take steps to reduce
restrictions on the mainland's exports to Taiwan, and to gradually
decrease the trade deficit with Taiwan to promote trade across the
Taiwan Straits in a healthy way.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that the trend in more exchanges and cooperation
across the Taiwan Straits cannot be stopped by any force at a time
when the situation of mutual promotion and mutual benefit exists
and when economic exchanges are being conducted on a fairly large
scale.
</P>
<P>
He quoted President Jiang Zemin as saying that for the growth
of the world economy in the 21st century, exchanges and
cooperation across the Taiwan Straits will benefit common
prosperity and bring happiness to the entire Chinese nation.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that "we will not affect or interrupt
cross-straits economic cooperation with political differences, but
rather will promote such relationships by encouraging Taiwan
business people's investment and follow the law of protecting
Taiwan compatriots' investment and expand trade as well."
</P>
<P>
"We will protect their just and reasonable rights and
interests," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
