<HEADLINE> Ulster Catholic Church Destroyed in Arson Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A Roman Catholic church in Northern
Ireland was destroyed early today in the fifth arson attack on
church property in a week, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Fire crews were unable to save the Mullavilly Church at
Tandragee in the border county of Armagh after it was set alight
at 0200 GMT today.
</P>
<P>
In the last week, a Catholic church in County Antrim and a
Baptist church in east Belfast have been destroyed by fire.
</P>
<P>
A second Catholic church in County Antrim and a Church of
Ireland hall in County Tyrone both survived arson attacks.
</P>
<P>
Of all the five damaged churches, three belong to the
province's Roman Catholic minority while the other two serve the
pro-British Protestant majority.
</P>
<P>
These incidents happened against a background of rising tension
in the province caused by guerrilla violence and the start of
Northern Ireland's marching season.
</P>
<P>
The Irish Republican Army (IRA), which has been fighting for
more than 25 years to end British rule in Ulster, was blamed for
last weekend's bomb scare that wrecked the Grand National horse
race and also for two other bomb alerts on British motorway last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Both Protestant and Roman Catholic churches' spokesmen have
condemned the arson attacks on their property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
