<HEADLINE> Mozambique Not to Attend COMESA Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique said today it will not
attend the second summit of the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) to be held in Lusaka, capital of Zambia
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Mozambican Minister of Foreign Affairs
and Cooperation Leonardo Simao here, according to the Mozambique
Information Agency.
</P>
<P>
Simao said, "we have suspended from attending activities of
the COMESA. We have informed the COMESA secretariat our decision
to withdraw from the organization."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the decision by the Mozambican government
was aimed at devoting its energy to the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), in which Mozambique began to assume
the post of its vice-chairman since 1996.
</P>
<P>
A number of the 12 SADC members are also members of the
20-nation COMESA. Like Mozambique, Lesotho and some other SADC
countries have also showed their desire to quit the COMESA, the
report said. 
