<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets With French Officials (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin,
meeting with French Defence Minister Charles Millon and French
Ambassador to China Pierre Morel in Beijing today, said that
China, after serious study, is ready to sign the UN's
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights
before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
So far, concerned departments are doing studies on domestic
legislation related to the covenant.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said he highly values French President Jacques Chirac's
decision that France will no longer take part in presenting bills
against China on human rights, and that he appreciates this
independent action by France.
</P>
<P>
Calling it a wise and far-sighted decision, Jiang said that it
shows France has an independent foreign policy of peace and shows
French determination in developing the Sino-French partnership. He
said he is convinced that this will have an important and positive
influence on the overall development of Sino-French relations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed out that China has, all along, taken an active
part in the UN's efforts to promote and protect human rights, and
highly values the significance of the UN's human rights
conventions in this regard, and that China has participated in 17
international human rights conventions.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We evaluated the International Covenant on Economic,
Social, and Cultural Rights and the International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights repeatedly." He pointed out that,
after serious study, China is ready to sign the UN's International
Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights before the end of
the year, and that related departments are studying domestic
legislation related to this covenant.
</P>
<P>
In keeping with the principle of universality in human rights
and China's domestic conditions, the Chinese government has made
efforts to achieve its own people's rights to subsistence and
development, and has raised the level of Chinese people's
economic, social, and cultural rights, Jiang noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, China has continued to improve the
development of democracy and a legal system to ensure Chinese
citizens' civil and political rights, and that the Chinese people
in fact enjoy comprehensive human rights.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that it is normal and inevitable that different
views on human rights exist in different countries because of
differences in social systems, economic development, historical
backgrounds, and cultural tradition. There is no wonder that there
are disputes, he said, but that what is more important is the way
these disputes are resolved.
</P>
<P>
Jiang emphasized that China has always held that the human
rights issue can only be solved through dialogue and exchanges
that are based on equality and mutual respect, and that China has
held several rounds of dialogues with the European Union, and will
continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
Noting that some western countries are still considering
presenting bills that go against China, Jiang said he hopes that
France can continue to play a constructive role in getting more
western countries take a proper stand to end confrontation and
move towards dialogue and cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chance of Fokker's Restart "Negligible" as Rescurer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The fate of the bankrupt Dutch
aircraft builder Fokker seemed to be finally sealed today after
one of the key parties in rescue talks pulled out and even its
receivers said a relaunch now looked impossible.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch engineering group Stork, which owns the profitable
Fokker aircraft maintenance and components units, announced it was
no longer bound by a memorandum of understanding, signed in March
as the blueprint of a possible resurrection.
</P>
<P>
"Stork has informed the Dutch state, the Deleye Investment
Group and the administrators that it is no longer bound by the
memorandum," Fokker's receiver said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The Fokker administrators have now concluded that any chance
of a restart definitely seems negligible," the document said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made after the failure of Malaysia's state
investment arm Khazanah Holdings Berhad to guarantee sufficient
financial support.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch aircraft maker collapsed a year ago, folding the
three units that made up 90 percent of its activities.
</P>
<P>
KLM and other airlines gave Fokker several aircraft orders to
keep it going until a rescuer could be found.
</P>
<P>
But the last three planes are nearly completed and many
employees have left in recent weeks, receivers said
</P>
<P>
Without the Malaysian deal, the plant is now expected to be
closed for good this summer and the assets liquidated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets With French Officials (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang said that since French President Jacques Chirac assumed
office, Sino-French friendship and cooperation have seen new
development, and that he is looking forward to Chirac's visit to
China this May, and that China attaches great importance to the
visit and is speeding up preparations.
</P>
<P>
He said he is convinced that this visit will have achieve
positive results in political, economic, and other areas.
</P>
<P>
During that visit, China and France will release a joint
statement making clear their common views on major international
issues and their common aspirations for further expanding
bilateral relations between China and France.
</P>
<P>
Jiang went on to say that both China and France shoulder
important responsibilities in international affairs, treasure
their national independence, and share identical views on many
major international issues.
</P>
<P>
"We favor a multi-polar world rather than a single-pole world,
one that is conducive not only to world peace, stability and
security, but also to the common development of the economies of
all the countries in the world," Jiang said, adding that there are
broad prospects for Sino-French economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At a time when the world is moving toward multi-polarization
while maintaining diversification, China and France should
strengthen exchanges and cooperation with an eye toward the future
from a strategic height, to set up long-term, stable, and new
relations of friendship and cooperation oriented to the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also said that the Chinese government agrees to increase
exchanges between the armed forces of the two countries in a bid
to safeguard world peace.
</P>
<P>
Millon said that President Chirac attaches great importance to
the development of relations with China. He also said that both
France and China have important responsibilities for safeguarding
world peace and promoting economic development, and follow
independent foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
Strengthening bilateral cooperation in various areas has a
practical significance in promoting and acceleration
multi-polarization of the world, Millon noted.
</P>
<P>
While saying that France is willing to increase bilateral
cooperation in the economy, trade, science, technology, and
culture, Millon said that his country is also willing to maintain
friendly cooperation with China in security and defense, and hopes
that both sides can have more exchanges of high-level visits and
strategic dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Through joint efforts, he said, the friendship and cooperation
between France and China can turn a new page in history.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his pleasure at hearing that China intends to sign
the International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights.
</P>
<P>
Millon conveyed Chirac's greetings to Jiang, and Jiang asked
Millon to convey his regards to Chirac in return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
