<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Labor Leads Conservatives by 21 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition Labor Party
still enjoys a 21-point lead over the ruling Conservatives with
just 23 days to go to the May 1 election, according to a leading
poll organization NOP poll released today.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted for Reuters news agency last Friday, said
the lead is down from 25 percentage points in the previous Reuters
poll conducted three weeks earlier, and just below the level shown
in two other polls published in newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The key thing is that although the lead has narrowed, the
change is not statistically significant," Reuters quoted Nick
Moon, head of political research at the polling organization NOP,
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Among the 1,088 sample voters, 51 percent said they would vote
for the Labor, while 30 percent favored for the Conservatives.
Eleven percent of the voters said they were ready to vote for the
minority Liberal Democratic party.
</P>
<P>
If the electorate cast its votes in line with this poll, Labor
would have 440 members in the 659-seat lower House of Commons, and
the Conservatives 169 seats. The Liberals would have 24 seats,
according to election experts' calculations.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that the Conservatives are starting to benefit
from a growing perception the economy is doing well, but not
enough to repair their damaged reputation for economic competence.
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives, ruling the country for the past 18 years,
have been racked by the slip of the party members on Europe
policies and hit hard by the involvement of the Conservative MPs
in financial and sexual scandals.
</P>
<P>
On the UK's relationship with Europe, the Labor Party has more
trust than the Conservatives. The poll shows 33 percent credited
Labor and 29 trusted the Conservatives in that respect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
