<HEADLINE> IBM to Enter TV Broadcasting Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Business
Machines Corp. (IBM), the world's leading computer maker, is
jumping into the market for television broadcasting equipment, the
Wall Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
The company is joining other computer companies such as
Microsoft in the emerging market, hoping to profit as the TV
industry moves to digital standards.
</P>
<P>
IBM plans to announce today that it will supply digital
production and transmission equipment for cable-TV systems,
broadcast-TV stations and satellite-broadcasting purveyors.
</P>
<P>
But the company will face some competitors in the
broadcast-equipment business, including Sony Corp. It also will be
up against its traditional opponents in the computer industry,
including Hewlett-Packard Co., which also see the TV industry's
move to digital technology as a potentially juicy new market.
</P>
<P>
IBM has already sold a digital-TV setup to an Italian telephone
company, which has been using it since last September to operate a
cable-TV network in Rome, it was reported. That setup converts the
digital signals back to analog, so customers can use their
conventional TV sets, through a special electronic box atop the
sets.
</P>
<P>
But IBM says it has the technology to adapt to all-digital
systems, such as those envisioned for the U.S. market starting
in late 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
