<HEADLINE> African Anaesthetists Urged to Come Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbafwean Vice-president Simon
Muzenda today urged African anaesthetists meeting in Harare to
pool their resources, particularly in the professional economic
field, in line with current international trends.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda said it had been proven that if people organized
themselves into bigger groups, they stood to gain, especially in
the economic field.
</P>
<P>
Opening a four-day All Africa Anaesthetic Congress, Muzenda
said, "for example, if an essential drug list, such as we have in
this country, were compiled for anaesthesia and anaesthetic
related drugs which were acceptable to a whole vast area of
Africa, that area would then become a desirable market."
</P>
<P>
If huge sales were made, the cost of the drugs would fall,
benefiting all, including the pharmaceutical companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said a regional grouping would also benefit anaesthetists
in the field of education.
</P>
<P>
He said because rewards outside the universities were great,
many academics were always leaving for greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
Academics, particularly in medicine, made considerable
financial sacrifices in order to study their subjects and teach
the subjects to the leaders of tomorrow, he said.
</P>
<P>
The congress is being attended by anaesthetists from all over
the world and is the first to be held in Africa. 
