<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recession Years Cost British People A Lot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The wealth-shrinking effect of the
recession has wiped 6,000 pounds (9,600 US dollars) off the
average Britons' net worth during the past seven years, figures
published today show.
</P>
<P>
According to independent analyst Datamonitor, from a peak in
1989, wealth per head has fallen, in real terms, from 31,851
pounds (50,961 dollars) to 25,442 pounds (40,707 dollars) last
year.
</P>
<P>
Britons are shown as thriftier than in the past and concerned
to stash away money for retirement, with an "earnest" attempt to
accumulate assets.
</P>
<P>
But, as the value of savings plans has grown, the recession has
cut an average of nearly 1,000 pounds (1,600 dollars) from each
person's net worth for every year since the boom.
</P>
<P>
These figures, from Datamonitor, come hard on the heels of
Sunday's publication of the 1997 edition of the Sunday Times' top
500 "rich list," which detected record numbers of billionaires and
multi-millionaires.
</P>
<P>
Those listed, the newspaper said, had seen an overall 23
percent rise in their wealth during the year.
</P>
<P>
Datamonitor said the collapse in average personal wealth was
due in large part to the slump in the property market. Real wealth
per head, said Datamonitor, was still below even the levels seen
in the crisis year 1992.
</P>
<P>
On paper, wealth per head stands at 39,855 pounds (63,768
dollars), against 36,751 pounds (58,802 dollars) in 1989.
</P>
<P>
But, with inflation taken into account, the figures are 25,442
pounds (40,707 dollars) and 31,851 pounds (50,961 dollars)
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Datamonitor said, "This drop was mostly due to decrease in
property prices, which have a dramatic effect on the value of net
asset holdings."
</P>
<P>
Harsha Yogasundram, an analyst of Datamonitor, said the trend
should be reversed over the next few years as the property market
recovers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
