<HEADLINE> Blood Donor Selection Crucial to Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Transmission of diseases through
blood transfusion could be reduced by improving donor selection,
screening of blood and cutting down on the number of unnecessary
transfusion, a world health organization (WHO) official said.
</P>
<P>
addressing the All Africa Anaesthetic Congress in harare
today, John Emmanuel said governments had the responsibility to
ensure safe blood while a non-governmental organization could be
delegated to manage the transfusion service.
</P>
<P>
''Each country should develop a national blood transfusion
plan so that the aims and objectives are adhered to in the
establishment of a coordinated blood transfusion program,'' said
Emmanuel.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference which opened here comes at a time when
Zimbabwe has made impressive improvements in protecting the blood
supply from transmitting infectious agents, despite the limits of
technology.
</P>
<P>
''The serious threat of infection to the recipients of blood
and blood products has highlighted the state of development of
blood transfusion services,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He said a national blood transfusion program could only be
sustainable if the country's health care and socio-economic
factors were taken into account during the planning and
development phase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
