<HEADLINE> Africa's Debt Equals to Continent's Combined GDP: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The OAU chief today said the
stock of Africa's debt is now almost equivalent to the combined
gross domestic product of the continent while the debt burden has
already exceeded 25 percent of Africa's export earnings.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Salim Ahmed Salim, Secretary-General
of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) when he was addressing
the opening session of the 20th ordinary session of the OAU labor
and social affairs commission here.
</P>
<P>
Salim said, the excessive accumulation of the excruciating
external debt of about 340.5 billion Dollars and an annual debt
service of about 24 billion Dollars continues to further
exacerbate foreign exchange constraints.
</P>
<P>
He called on both African countries and creditor countries
''to undertake bold and courageous steps aimed at alleviating the
Africa's debt burden''.
</P>
<P>
''Time has come for our partners in the developed world to
realize that the external debt is strangling our economies and
our countries development efforts and to recognize that Africa
deserves a special treatment in a spirit of genuine cooperation,
solidarity and long term mutual benefit,'' he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Salim described employment crisis as ''one of the most serious
challenges facing African continent in the social sector''.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''the employment situation in Africa which had
deteriorated considerably over the past fifteen years continued
to be grim in most of our countries with urban unemployment rates
estimated in the 15 to 20 percent range; under-employment rates
in the 25 to 50 percent; youth unemployment rates in the 25 to 40
percent range; while women unemployment range was twice the
national average.''
</P>
<P>
''Against the backdrop of this employment situation, unless
determined and improved employment and development policies are
implemented, the employment crisis is likely to be aggravated up
to the year 2000 with labor force growth rate rising about 2.8
percent and out-passing annual employment growth rate of 2.3
percent,'' he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
On the protection of child and elimination of child labor in
Africa, Salim said it is estimated that about 24 million children
in Africa are forced to sacrifice their health, their education,
their childhood and formative years, in a daily struggle for
survival in violation of national legislation and international
labor standards.
</P>
<P>
The six-day meeting following discussions on the social and
economic issues of the continent, is expected to come up with
proposals that could help alleviate the complex problems of the
African people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
