<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Turns Eye on Terminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Microsoft Corp., the world's
software giant, is turning its ears to the call for simpler
computers.
</P>
<P>
U.S. newspapers reported today that the company has begun
developing technology for what it calls Windows Terminal, a
desktop machine with no disk drive or stored software of its own.
Its software and files would be executed on a computer called a
server, with which the terminal would communicate over computer
networks.
</P>
<P>
"So that's a machine you never have to replace until there's
some radical change in the way that people interact with the
computers," said Bill Gates, chairman of Microsoft, in a speech
last week.
</P>
<P>
The concept is strikingly similar to a machine that Oracle
Corp. and others have called as a network computer (NC).
</P>
<P>
Desktop personal computer is known for its great flexibility
and efficiency. But the idea of centralizing computing resources
is beginning to regain momentum.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft's shift, mentioned by Bill Gates, comes as Oracle
prepares to ship two long-awaited pieces of software that will be
used to power the network computers.
</P>
<P>
Oracle also plans to disclose soon its first substantial NC
order with a New York based company. Sun Microsystems Inc. and
International Business Machines Corp. also are big proponents of
NCs, which are expected to cost 500 to 1,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft has long resisted the NC concept as one that could
reduce the need for companies to buy its operating systems and
applications software.
</P>
<P>
A research company predicts that NC sales to companies will
swell from 1.7 million units this year to 6.7 million by 2000.
Another research firm found that 58 percent of major corporations
it surveyed are evaluating NCs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
