<HEADLINE> UN Appeals for 126.2 Mln Dlrs to Aid DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- UN Under-Secretary-General
Yasushi Akashi today called for 126.2 million dollars to meet
urgent humanitarian needs in the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The appeal was based on proposals by the World Food Program,
the United Nations Development Program, the United Nations
Children's Fund, the Food and Agriculture Organization and the
World Health Organization. It covered the period from April 1997
through March 1998, according to Akashi.
</P>
<P>
It focused on urgent needs in three priority sectors, resulting
from the effects of unprecedented flooding in the DPRK in 1995 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
The leading sector was food aid to meet the most urgent need
with an estimated expenditure over 95 million dollars. UN agencies
noted that the food situation in the DPRK has deteriorated with a
current grain shortfall of 2.36 million metric tons. The food aid
was aimed at providing nutritional support for children under six,
for hospitals and food for work projects.
</P>
<P>
The other priority sectors were food security for resuming
normal food production at a cost of nearly 21 million dollars and
restoration of basic health services which would need 9 million
dollars. 
</P>
