<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Bill to Be Tabled to Kenyan Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government would take
tough actions against tobacco advertizing, smoking in public
places and cigarette sales to under-18s if the Tobacco Control
Bill is passed at the current parliamentary session.
</P>
<P>
The bill to be debated at the last session of the seventh
parliament will require cigarette manufacturers to disclose the
tar and nicotine content of their products and to list diseases
related with smoking.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, the nicotine standard for cigarettes
sold in Kenya is at a maximum rate of 2.2 miligrams per cigarette
and the cigarette packets should carry "low", "medium" and "high"
tar designations.
</P>
<P>
Punitive measures will be taken against smoking in such public
places as restaurants, buses, ships and aircraft flying internal
routes.
</P>
<P>
Selling cigarettes to those under 18 years will incur a
maximum fine of 10,000 Kenyan Shillings (about 178 U.S. Dollars)
or two months in jail.
</P>
<P>
The bill also says that cigarette advertizements will not be
allowed to run in the general media without the Health Ministry's
approval.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a curriculum to educate the youth against
cigarette and alcohol consumption was intended to be introduced
into the Kenyan primary and secondary school education system.
</P>
<P>
At present, it is being implemented on a pilot basis in some
schools in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
The legislation comes at a time when tobacco multi-nationals
are joined in a fierce battle for Kenya's 178 million Dollars
cigarette market with an advertizing and promotion blitz and
widening sports sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
Among the entrants in the past six months are U.S. giants R.J.
Reynolds, makers of the Aspen brand, and Phillip Morris, whose
top-selling brand is Marlboro.
</P>
<P>
Facing increasing restrictions and dwindling markets in the
United States, the American companies came to Kenya to gain a
foothold in emerging markets in the Third World. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
