<HEADLINE> COMESA Council of Ministers Meet in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The third meeting of the Council
of Ministers of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA) opened here today to make preparations for the COMESA
summit to be held here later this week.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day meeting, the ministers will discuss issues of
trade and customs, transport and communications, industry, energy
and environment as well as work program and priorities of the
COMESA members states for 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of regional and international organizations
were also present at the opening meeting.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Zambian Vice President Godfrey Miyanda
expressed his hope that the meeting will provide the framework
for ensuring that COMESA effectively becomes the gateway to
economic integration, growth and development into the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
He said that adequate preparations shall be made for the
COMESA summit to be held on Thursday this week.
</P>
<P>
"The strengthening of COMESA is an indispensable necessity in
view of the challenges of globalization and the emergence of
powerful regional trading blocks in other parts of the world,"
said Miyanda.
</P>
<P>
He called for maintenance of peace and security in the region,
saying that meaningful development could not be achieved without
peace and security.
</P>
<P>
He said that quick resolutions of conflicts in some COMESA
members countries should be sought.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda emphasized the need to complete the program for the
realization of a free trade area by the year 2000, noting that
"the establishment of a free trade area in COMESA by the year
2000 will have far-reaching implications for trade and investment
in infrastructure, production and service-relation industries."
</P>
</TEXT>
