<HEADLINE> Kenya's Economic Reform Aimed at Enhancing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Finance Minister Musalia Mudavadi
today said Kenya's economic reforms are aimed at enhancing the
private sector in the economy, according to a Kenya News Agency
report today.
</P>
<P>
Opening the 72nd Rotary International District Conference in
port city Mombasa, he stated that the government confines itself
to those activities which it alone can perform well.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that efforts of the Kenyan government to
create an enabling environment for enterprises are now beginning
to yield results.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that inflation had been brought under control,
the Shilling's exchange rate had stabilized and the country's
foreign exchange reserves increased substantially to a
comfortable level.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth in gross domestic product increased from
0.2 percent in 1993 to 4.9 percent in 1995, which is seen as a
great achievement to Kenya, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mudavadi said the government is conscious of the adverse
effects of the Structural Adjustment Program affecting the common
people.
</P>
<P>
To shield the poor people, he stressed, the government has
designed social dimensions of development program and other
initiatives to cater for their needs.
</P>
<P>
The launching of the National Youth Development Fund is
designed to promote self-employment among the youth to address
their problems, he pointed out. 
</P>
