<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Continues to Drop in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Governor of the Bank of
Tanzania (BOT) Idris Rashidi today said he is optimistic the rate
of inflation will reach 5 percent within the next 15 months.
</P>
<P>
He made this predication at a banker's conference at
Arusha in northern Tanzania, attributing the on-going decline of
inflation in Tanzania to improved tax collection, government
austerity and favorable external conditions such as stable oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
"If we go on with implementing 'sensible' fiscal and monetary
policies, we will reach the 5 percent target by June 1998, or
earlier," the governor said in a keynote address to the
conference.
</P>
<P>
Rashidi noted that the government is striving to live within
its means through a cash-budget system introduced in May 1995,
under which expenditure was matched to revenue collections.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "this very sensible and simple system has
eliminated central bank lending to the government. In other
words, it has eradicated a practice of printing money as a source
of funding the government. And as a result, inflation has
declined precipitously".
</P>
<P>
He further said that a modest economic growth influenced the
slowdown of inflation.
</P>
<P>
"The agricultural sector, which accounts for 55 percent of
total GDP, increased by 7.0 percent," the governor observed,
saying, "as a result of improved agricultural performance,
average food price inflation during the year ended February, 1997
rose by 14 percent against an increase of 25 percent registered a
year earlier."
</P>
<P>
He said a strict monetary policy that aimed at checking excess
liquidity in the economy worked well in curbing inflation,
because money supply in the economy has been significantly
controlled.
</P>
<P>
Rashidi added that external conditions were also favorable,
saying that there was no major increase in oil prices nor
generalized increases in prices of Tanzania's major imports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
