<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Reaffirms Support for Freezing Jewish Settlements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- France today reaffirmed its wish for
a freezing of Israel's Jewish settlements in the Palestinian
territories of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip, as well as its
opposition to a new housing project by Israel in Har Homa district
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
France also hopes that the United States will "respond
positively" to a proposed joint initiative by the United States
and the European Union (EU) on the relaunching of the peace
process in the Middle East, said French Foreign Ministry spokesman
Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that our actions (between the United States and the
European Union) should be convergent and complementary," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry officials of EU countries decided in Brussels
Monday to propose to Washington a joint initiative to help
relaunch the Middle East peace process, which has now entered an
impasse following the Israeli decision to build the Har Homa
housing project with 6,500 flats.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu, now on a visit in
Washington, has ruled out the possibility of freezing Jewish
settlements in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip, or stopping the
building of the Har Homa settlement.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested the holding of a 1978 David Camp style
tripartite meeting by the United States, Israel and Palestinians
on the resumption of peace talks between the Jewish state and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was judged as "premature" by U.S. President Bill
Clinton, who said Monday that he would like to have dialogue with
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The EU envoy for the Middle East, Miguel Angel Moratinos, will
meet with French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette today in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
De Charette said in an interview with a local newspaper, La
Charente Libre, that Europe "should play an active role by
exercising necessary pressure (on Israel) so that the peace
process could resume."
</P>
<P>
But he ruled out the possibility of imposing economic sanctions
on Israel as a way to exert such pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
