<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Not Enthusiastic About Immediate Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said here today that an Arab summit is yet to be convened at a
right timing, but not now.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt believes that Arab leaders will not tarry in responding
to a call for holding an Arab summit if there is need for such a
meeting," he said.
</P>
<P>
In statements to reporters after his visit to two high-tech
centers in the capital, Mubarak hailed the lastest Arab League
Council meeting, which has have approved a resolution recommending
Arabs to freeze normalization steps and resume economic boycott
against Israel.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting last week, the Arabs, for the first time
since hardline Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu took
power last June, agreed to orchestrate concerted positions against
the construction for 6,500 homes for Jews in East Jerusalem, an
Israeli move that has stranded the already-sluggish peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu's insistence on continuing the controversial
project prompted calls for convening another Arab summit to force
Israel to comply.
</P>
<P>
Asked for his view on a meeting between Netanyahu and
U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington, Mubarak sounded a
rather conservative tone and said he has not been informed of the
outcome yet.
</P>
<P>
"Let us wait and see what the current contacts will lead to,"
he said of the Netanyahu visit, which was arranged hastily in hope
of reviving the disrupted Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the same vein on Monday, the Egyptian leader
expressed reserved optimism that Clinton could persuade Netanyahu
to stop the settlement building.
</P>
<P>
"If the American initiative could succeed in convincing
Netanyahu, it would be a step ahead... But we'd better wait and
see," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, blaming Palestinian violence for the peace crisis
and refusing to halt the Jewish settlement building, flew to the
U.S. Sunday to seek backing for his offer to seal a final peace
with the Palestinians within six months.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians have refused to resume talks or security
cooperation with Israel unless the construction in East Jerusalem
and expansion of Jewish settlements in the West Bank stop.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration hopes to bring the two sides to
face-to-face talks with a new initiative aimed to press Netanyahu
to stop the settlement building and to urge Arafat to curb
Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, a longtime critic of Israel's hardline policies,
however, ruled out the possibility of cutting ties with Israel,
saying that it would not serve peace if Egypt, a key mediator in
the peace process, stops contacts with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
An intensive U.S.-Egyptian-Israeli summit at the Camp David,
the U.S., in 1978, led to a peace treaty between Egypt and
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
