<HEADLINE> KEDO Mission Leaves S.Korea for DPRK Direct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A 54-member team from the Korean
Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO) left South Korea
today for the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) to
negotiate the building of nuclear reactors in the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The KEDO team left the eastern port of Tonghae, South Korea,
aboard a trainer ship of the South Korean Maritime University at
6:00 p.m. (0900 GMT), and sailed directly for the DPRK. This was
the first sea-route trip between South Korea and the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the KEDO group and DPRK officials will focus
on preparations for ground breaking to build two 1,000-megawatt
light-water reactors in Shinpo, on the northeastern coast of the
DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The delegation was headed by KEDO deputy executive director,
South Korea's Choi Young-jin, and was composed of 40 South
Koreans, three United States delegates, three Japanese and eight
KEDO staff.
</P>
<P>
During their stay in the DPRK between April 9 to 15, the
delegation will survey the infrastructure for building the
reactors.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss the implementation of the the five
protocols concluded with Pyongyang on inter-Korean communication,
and the utility of DPRK's human and material resources as well as
other social services.
</P>
<P>
The problem of transportation for the nuclear project is also
likely to be mentioned because South Korea regards the sea route
direct delivery as a good option.
</P>
<P>
The week-long discussion will be the first in a series of talks
which are expected before actual ground breaking for the
construction of the nuclear reactors, officials of South Korea's
office for the light-water nuclear project said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
