<HEADLINE> Americans, Canadians Divided Over Anti-Cuba Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Canadians and Americans are deeply
divided over the United States' trade policy against Cuba, an
Angus Reid poll shows.
</P>
<P>
About 48 percent of Americans who responded to the poll opposed
the Helms-Burton Act, which penalizes foreign companies who do
business with Cuba, while 45 percent said they favored it,
according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted in March, surveyed 1,000 Canadians and
1,004 Americans. The error margin was 3.1.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade law is less popular in Canada, with 79 percent
of the Canadians polled saying that they were opposed to the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
John Wright, vice-president of the Angus Reid Group, said he
was surprised that so few Americans supported the Helms-Burton law.
</P>
<P>
"I would say there's a lot of fodder here for debate," the
Ottawa Citizen newspaper quoted Wright as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It shows the Chretien government is on track in terms of
foreign policy in this country, and there could be some sympathy
in the U.S. for our position."
</P>
<P>
Canada, which has broad trade links with Cuba, has been in the
forefront of the fight against the Helms-Burton Act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
