<HEADLINE> German Workers Protest NATO Job Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- About 7,000 German civilian workers
demonstrated today in the southwestern city of Kaiserslautern in
protest against threatened job cuts by North Atlantic Treaty
Organization bases.
</P>
<P>
At dispute are plans of the United States military and other
NATO troops stationed in Germany to cut back their local service
work forces following the reduction of the troops after the end of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 12,000 local workers could lose
their jobs this year out of the total of 35,000 currently hired by
the military bases of the United States, Britain, France and
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, about 100,000 local German civilian workers were hired
by NATO military bases in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations were organized by the German trade union for
public service and transport, the OETV, and the employees' trade
union, the DAG, German media reports said.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 buses and private cars carried the demonstrators
to Kaiserslautern, where the largest U.S. garrison in Europe is
located.
</P>
<P>
The OETV chairman, Herbert Mai, called on the German civilian
workers to continue their strikes which began five weeks ago and
were suspended during Easter.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a job protection agreement at the next round
of negotiations with military employers scheduled for April 16-17
in Koblenz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
