<HEADLINE> Russian FM Arrives in Paris to Discuss Russia-NATO Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni
Primakov arrived here this afternoon for a two-day visit, during
which he will discuss with French leaders the relations between
Russia and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Primakov will meet with Prime Minister Alain Juppe and Foreign
Minister Herve de Charette this afternoon, and President Jacques
Chirac Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Their talks will be focused on the details of NATO's eastward
expansion plan, which France supports, and the envisaged charter
between NATO and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The NATO Madrid summit to be held on July 8-9 will decide on
which central and eastern European nations will be absorbed by
NATO in the first wave of its expansion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the Russian news agency ITAR-TASS, Russia and NATO
could sign a charter specifying their relations by the end of May
in Paris.
</P>
<P>
However, a French Foreign Ministry spokesman said that it is
still too early to fix the date and venue for the signing of such
a charter, which is designed to install a privileged forum of
dialogue between the two former enemies during the Cold War, and
to alleviate Russian hostility toward NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
France has expressed its understanding of Russia's worry over
NATO expansion, which Moscow thinks would create a new division in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac said in Prague last week that
NATO should convince Russia that its expansion would not make up a
humiliation or threat for Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
