<HEADLINE> Grace Period Extended for China's Overseas-funded Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- China's State Council has decided
to extend a grace period by one year for taxes paid by certain
overseas-funded enterprises on imported equipment and materials.
</P>
<P>
According to a previous decision of the State Council, certain
overseas-funded enterprises set up before March 31, 1996 would
enjoy a grace period on imported equipment and raw materials until
December 31, 1996, but that any projects set up after April 1,
1996 would be subject to normal tariffs on imported equipment and
raw materials.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release from the State Council today,
overseas-funded enterprises that have already been approved for
the grace period will get an extension to December 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises are defined to be those that involve a total
overseas investment of less than 30 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the news release, the enterprises must have been
approved by local governments and filed with the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) before September
30, 1995, or have been approved by local governments and passed
assessment by the MOFTEC, the State Planning Commission (SPC) and
the State Economic and Trade Commission (SETC) between October 1,
1995 and March 31, 1996. They need to pass annual assessments by
the MOFTEC, SPC, and SETC for 1997 also.
</P>
<P>
The decision is intended to allow enterprises that have already
been set up to continue operation and production according to
their initial plans and feasibility studies, and to safeguard the
interest of overseas investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
