<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Project Hope Raises Nearly A Billion Yuan in 8 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Project Hope, the national
fund-raising program to help students in poverty-stricken areas,
has collected 978 million yuan over the past eight years, allowing
1.5 million poor youngsters to return to school.
</P>
<P>
The figures come from Liu Peng, chairman of the Board of the
Chinese Youth Development Foundation, who spoke with Xinhua
today. Since 1987, he said, when the organization was founded, it
has helped build over 3,600 Hope primary schools and 10,000 Hope
libraries for village primary schools, and more than 3,000 primary
school teachers have been given rewards or have been provided with
training by project funds.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, Project Hope had helped build or plan at
least one primary school for each of the nearly 600 poor counties
in China.
</P>
<P>
Beginning this year, he said, the national program plans to
start a new round of fund-raising efforts since the government has
set a goal of "basically popularizing nine-year compulsory
education" and "basically solving the problem of food and clothing
for 58 million poor people" by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
This year, Project Hope plans to raise 500 million yuan, help
300,000 dropouts, and build 1,000 Hope primary schools, he said,
noting that a nationwide fund-raising campaign will begin in May.
</P>
<P>
Project Hope will mainly collect donations through banks and a
deal has been made with the China Construction Bank and the
Agricultural Bank of China for this. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
