<HEADLINE> Manila Confirms Rebel Leader's Order to Renew Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary Renato
de Villa confirmed here today that he has also received
information that exiled New People's Army leader Jose Sison has
ordered his fighters to intensify attacks against the government.
</P>
<P>
De Villa said Sison issued the order to the New People's Army,
the National Democratic Front's military branch, on March 29
during the anniversary of the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
However, de Villa said the peace process between the government
and the NDF in the Netherlands is still on. The two sides are
reported to have reached three agreements and are expected to
conclude their talks in June this year.
</P>
<P>
With Sison's order to step up attacks, the military chief said
that government troops have been told to be careful.
</P>
<P>
"Our troops in the field have been advised accordingly that
there is such an order from the New People's Army leadership," de
Villa said.
</P>
<P>
De Villa declined to speculate on any deadlock in the on-going
talks but expressed the hope that the NDF will negotiate in good
faith and try to help everyone arrive at a mutually acceptable
term.
</P>
<P>
Former Senator Rodolfo Biazon, a consultant to the government
panel negotiating with the NDF, chided Sison for calling for
renewed attacks against the government.
</P>
<P>
He said Sison's battle orders were contained in a 13-page
message to the New People's Army "to intensify guerrilla warfare
on a wide scale on the basis of an ever-expanding and deepening
mass base."  
</P>
</TEXT>
