<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Revise Penal Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has urged
the legislature to revise the penal code in order to tackle
corruption, drug abuse and child sexual abuse more effectively.
</P>
<P>
Some articles of the present penal code, which exposed "many
mistakes and errors", will be considered and revised immediately
in order to serve the fight against crime, Justice Minister
Nguyen Dinh Loc said.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnam News Agency quoted him as saying that lack of
details and clear definition of corruption acts in the present law
hindered the effectiveness of the anti-corruption drive.
</P>
<P>
"This has caused many difficulties for the determination of
corrupt acts as well as punishment scales. This has also created
loopholes for legal abuses," Loc said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "almost all corruption-related offenses will
be given higher punishment scales and focus on individual
offenders."
</P>
<P>
On drug abuse, the minister said the revised law will give a
new chapter to drug-related crimes, as against the existing two
articles on narcotic production, trafficking and abuse in the
penal code.
</P>
<P>
To effectively prevent child sexual crimes, the revised code
will include a new article on the child sexual abuse with tough
punishment scales, the minister noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
