<HEADLINE> Wheat Supply to Be Improved Soon: Pak Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Agriculture Minister
Abida Hussain said here today the supply of wheat will be improved
in a couple of days while appealing people not to buy more than
necessary and not to hoard.
</P>
<P>
With the arrival of imported wheat at Karachi and start of
harvesting season in the provinces of Sindh and Punjab, the
availability of wheat has been started improving, Abida said at a
news conference here today.
</P>
<P>
She said one ship carrying 47,250 tons of wheat has docked at
Karachi and releasing wheat which was being transported to the
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Eight more ships carrying 378,000 tons of wheat would reach
Karachi in the next few days, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said by the time wheat in all the provinces would have been
harvested.
</P>
<P>
The position of wheat supply in other three provinces was under
control whereas there was a problem in North West Frontier
province which was due to reasons of logistics and distribution,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the situation in the NWFP was unfortunately being
multiplied by the blockage of roads and access to the flour mills,
she said. Forced closure of flour outlet and shops also created
problems for the government to ensure a smooth supply of wheat.
</P>
</TEXT>
