<HEADLINE> China's FM Spokesman Calls for Halt To Human Rights Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman
Shen Guofang today said that China hopes that those countries that
still insist on making an anti-China motion at the UN human rights
conference will decide to stop confrontation.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question at a press conference here, Shen said
that the decision taken by France, Germany, Italy, Spain, Greece,
and Japan not to support the anti-China motion at the UN Human
Rights Commission is a wise one.
</P>
<P>
He said that this decision is in keeping with the desires of
the majority of the countries attending the conference for holding
dialogues instead of confrontations.
</P>
<P>
Western nations, for six consecutive years, have presented
anti-China motions to the conference, but all of them have met
with a great deal of opposition, proving that confrontation won't
help solve problems, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said China hopes that those countries that persist in
putting forth anti-China motions will seriously consider the
appeals of the majority of the participants in the human rights
conference and change their position.
</P>
<P>
If certain countries insist on taking the lead in making
anti-China motions, their action will inevitably bring harm to the
bilateral relations and to the normal exchange in the human rights
field, the spokesman said. 
</P>
