<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Increases Russia's Steel Export Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BRUSSELS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
Russia have struck a new agreement on steel, paving the way for
the complete liberalization of bilateral trade in steel.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will allow Russia to increase sales to the EU
while gradually developing normal competitive conditions in its
steel industry, notably in competition policy, state aid and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, EU quotas will be raised by 10 percent in
1997, a further five percent increase in 1998 and 2.5 percent more
each year up to the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
This process could come forward depending on when Russia
applies competition, state aid and environmental disciplines
compatible with those in the EU.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the deal, Sir Leon Brittan, EU commissioner for
trade policy, said: ``This agreement shows Europe's commitment to
open markets and provides a strong incentive to Russia to build
its steel sector firmly on the principles of fair trade, rigorous
competition and a clean environment."
</P>
<P>
The new agreement with Russia will replace the 1995-96
agreement, which has been extended until June 30, 1997. It will
cover the period until December 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will be reviewed if Russia joins the World Trade
Organization before 2001.
</P>
<P>
It will be submitted for approval to the EU Council of
Ministers and the Russian government, and should come into force
in the autumn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
