<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Mad Cow Case Found in Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE HAGUE, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A second case of bovine
spongiform encephalopathey (BSE), or mad cow disease, has been
found in the Netherlands, just over two weeks after the first.
</P>
<P>
Dutch newspapers said on Tuesday that the disease was diagnosed
in a cow in the northern province of Friesland.
</P>
<P>
The first BSE case in the Netherlands was reported on March
21. The cow was slaughtered in late March and the Dutch
government has provided full details of the case to the European
Commission in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
As a precaution, the farm where the infected cow was detected
has been sealed off and all livestock there will be killed. The
slaughterhouse has also been closed and all its stocks of meat
will be destroyed, the government said.
</P>
<P>
The infection is a brain-wasting disease which has been linked
to a new strain of a fatal human equivalent called
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease.
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, about 178,000 BSE cases have been confirmed in the
European Union and Switzerland, according to figures published by
the European Commission. The majority of those cases -- around
172,000 -- have occurred in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands has also been struggling in recent weeks to
contain an outbreak of swine fever which has already led to a EU
export ban and the destruction of several thousand pigs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft Law on Position of Jonas Savimbi Adopted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan National Assembly
passed a draft law at a special meeting here today on the special
position of Jonas Savimbi, president of the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The draft law stipulates that Jonas Savimbi is the "leader of
the biggest opposition party in the country".
</P>
<P>
The law was adopted at the 47th meeting of the Joint Committee
for overseeing the peace process on March 21 after as long as
15-month discussions.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft law, Savimbi can freely engage in
political and party activities anywhere in the country and has
the right to "ask" for exchange of opinions with the president of
the Republic on matters concerning the politcal life of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The draft law also stipulates that Savimbi ranks second among
the leaders of the various parties in the assembly concerning
protocol. He also enjoys the same immunity and other privileges
with leaders of the state sovereign organs born through
elections.
</P>
<P>
The draft law was passed with 120 affirmative votes and 6
abstentions after one and a half hours discussion. The majority
of parliament members in their speeches expressed the view that
the adoption of this law was conducive to the realization of
peace and national reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
