<HEADLINE> KEDO Mission Leaves for DPRK Direct from S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A 54-member team of the Korean
Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO) left South Korea
today for the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) to
prepare for the building of nuclear reactors in the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The KEDO team left the eastern port of Tonghae, South Korea, by
ship at 6:00 p.m. (0900 GMT) directly for Shinpo on the
northeastern coast of the DPRK, where the reactor construction
site is located.
</P>
<P>
The mission will discuss with DPRK officials the implementation
of the the five protocols concluded with Pyongyang on
inter-Korean communication, and the utility of DPRK's human and
material resources as well as other social services.
</P>
<P>
The mission will also survey the infrastructure for building
light-water nuclear reactors in Shinpo.
</P>
<P>
The problem of transportation for the nuclear project is also
likely to be mentioned because South Korea regards the sea route
direct delivery as a good option. 
</P>
</TEXT>
