<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Peace in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen
Guofang said today that China has paid close attention to the
situation in Zaire, and sincerely hopes that the parties involved
will settle their dispute through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question at a press conference today, Shen said
that China, as a permanent member of the UN Security Council, has
taken an active part in UN discussions and consultations on the
Zairian conflict, and it backs a peaceful resolution to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
The conflict has brought deep suffering to the Zairian people
and to refugees in eastern Zaire, and is endangering the peace and
stability of the Great Lake region and the African continent as a
whole, Shen pointed out.
</P>
<P>
During a recent special summit meeting held by the Organization
of African Unity and attended by heads of state and government
leaders of a dozen African nations, UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, and OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim, efforts by
those involved helped the two sides in the dispute agree to hold
peace talks, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
South African leaders are now presiding over direct talks in
Pretoria between delegates from the two sides of the dispute,
according to the spokesman who said China hopes they will respond
to the appeal for peace by the international community and end the
dispute through negotiations at an early date to maintain national
unity and ethnic harmony, resume social stability, and work
together for the development of country.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates and backs the efforts of the OAU, the UN, and
other African countries to properly settle the dispute, Shen said,
and hopes the negotiations will be fruitful, so that peace in
Zaire will be realized and the people of the region will be free
from the suffering of war.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
