<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NAM Declaration on Reforms of United Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The 12th Non-Aligned Movement
(NAM) foreign ministers' conference here today adopted a
five-point declaration on the reform of the United Nations for
democratization of the world body.
</P>
<P>
"There shall be no partial or selective expansion or
enlargement of the membership of the Security Council, to the
detriment of developing countries," the declaration says.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts at restructuring the Security Council shall not be
subject to any imposed time-frame. While recognizing the
importance of treating this issue as a matter of urgent attention,
no effort should be made to decide this issue before general
agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers decided to remain seized of the issue and its
development which they review at their next annual meeting on the
occasion of the 52nd session of the UNGA.
</P>
<P>
"The use of the veto should be curtailed with a view to its
eventual elimination.
</P>
<P>
"The improvement of the working methods of the Security Council
should be given equal importance."
</P>
<P>
The NAM foreign ministers stressed in the declaration that at
this historic moment, the international community has a joint
responsibility to collectively reshape this unique world body to
meet the aspirations of all humanity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Street in East Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A street in Xiamen, a coastal city
in Fujian Province, just across the Straits from Taiwan, was
renamed "Taiwan Street" today, while local officials announced the
establishment of the Xiamen Taiwan Street Investment Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Local developers plan to use 2.6 billion yuan developing it
into a "multi-purpose service quarter for economic and other
exchanges across the Taiwan Straits," according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
The former Heshan Road, is 859 meters long and 40 meters wide,
and developers have leased 100 meters more on each side of the
street, and local builders expect to erect a high-rise office
tower and trade center with a full-range of services.
</P>
<P>
This commercial quarter has attracted the attention of overseas
investors and some real estate projects are underway.
</P>
<P>
The street is in the center of Xiamen Island. With its rapidly
improving infrastructure and public utilities, it is expected to
be popular with investors from Taiwan and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
According to city government statistics, the city attracted 370
million US dollars last year, up eight percent from the previous
year, and trade with Taiwan increased 27 percent to 1.6 billion
dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
