<HEADLINE> U.N. Appeals for More Aid for DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Several agencies of the United
Nations have appealed for more aid amounting to 126 million
U.S. dollars to meet urgent humanitarian needs in the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The previous appeal ended on March 31.
</P>
<P>
The new aid would cover the the period from April 1997 through
to March 1998, it was announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the money, about 76 percent, will be used to provide
food.
</P>
<P>
The money will also be used to help the DPRK resume normal food
production and restore basic health services.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was based on proposals by the World Food Program
(WFP), the U.N. Development Program, the U.N. Children's Fund, the
Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and the World Health
Organization.
</P>
<P>
According to FAO/WFP assessments, the food situation in the
DPRK has deteriorated dramatically since the previous appeal, with
a present grain shortfall of 2.36 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
