<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Population Rises to 18.28 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Up to June 30, 1996, the
estimated resident population of Australia was 18,289,000,
representing a national population growth rate of 1.3 percent
since June 30, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The net population gain from overseas migration was 114,170,
representing 48 percent of Australia's population growth, the
Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said in a bulletin today.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the United Kingdom was not the greatest
source of migrants to Australia, while another Western country,
New Zealand, not any Asian country, took the top spot as the
greatest migrant source.
</P>
<P>
Of the total migrants arriving in Australia in 1995-96, 12,300,
or 12 percent were New Zealanders, followed closely by Britons.
Coming a close third were Chinese-born migrants, whose number
included migrants from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Of last year's migrant intake, the fourth largest group was
from the former Yugoslav republics, many of whom arrived as
refugees or under the humanitarian program.
</P>
<P>
Migrant number from Vietnam and the Philippines continued to
decline last year. The Vietnamese figure dropped 30 percent to
3,600 and Filipinos 21 percent to 3,200.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
