<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Joint Venture In Castings For Automobiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Three enterprises from China and
the United States today signed a joint agreement here for a large
firm to produce castings for automobile engines.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Strategic Investment Management Co. (ASIMCO),
Caterpillar (China) Ltd., and China International Trust &AMP;
Investments Corp.'s Machinery &AMP; Manufacturing Co. (CMMI) agreed to
put 98.8 million US dollars into the Shanxi International Casting
Co., to be located some 600 kilometers from Beijing in Shanxi
province, which is rich in coal and iron ore resources.
</P>
<P>
ASIMCO will own 57 percent of the company, Caterpillar 21
percent, and CMMI the remaining 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
The company is scheduled to begin operation in the first
quarter of 1998, and is expected to produce 45,000 tons of
castings in the first phase, and another 40,000 tons after the
second phase.
</P>
<P>
ASIMCO already has 17 joint ventures in China, 13 of them in
auto parts and components.
</P>
<P>
CMMI is a large military-turned-civilian enterprise, and a
subsidiary of CITIC, with fixed assets totalling 1.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Caterpillar is one the world's major diesel engine suppliers,
with two joint ventures in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
