<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Continue Ban on Meat Import From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Agriculture Secretary
Salvador Escudero today announced anew the temporary ban on
importation of livestock, meat and meat products from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Escudero said in a statement the ban is necessary to ensure
that no infected-livestock or contaminated meat and meat products
enter the country.
</P>
<P>
Escudero also directed the Quarantine and Animal/Plant
Inspection in all major entry-exit points such as the
international airports and ports to implement appropriate measures
such as the foot baths to prevent the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
He said his department will not take any single risk of
endangering its livestock industry, particularly the hog industry
which suffered a major blow in 1995 due to the Foot-Mouth-Disease
(FMD) outbreaks in Luzon.
</P>
<P>
However, the Philippine Bureau of Animal Industry said the FMD
outbreak, which occurred in Taiwan on March 10, is quite different
from the FMD strains in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan has the so-called Asia I type FMD strain whereas in the
Philippines, there are three FMD strains, namely, O1, which is
similar to the Hong Kong FMD strain, and A24 and C3 of the South
American strains, the bureau said earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has immediately notified Taiwanese
authorities to stop all exportation of live pigs, meat and meat
products to the Philippines since the FMD outbreak started in
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is primarily importing pig skin and live
breeding animals such as swine from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the reported outbreak of Swine Fever in the
Netherlands and Germany also prompted the Philippines to ban the
importation of live pigs, pork and pork products from the
Netherlands and Germany.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
