<HEADLINE> China to Expand Asset, Capital Check-up Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- China will expand an experiment in
checking the asset value and capital stock of urban-based
collective enterprises, according to a national meeting that
opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The accounting effort is a primary effort to promote the reform
and development of the collective economy and to strengthen
enterprise management, said Zhang Youcai, deputy minister of
finance.
</P>
<P>
"The collective sector is an important basis of China's
socialist, public-owned economy and is a main part of the
socialist public ownership," he said.
</P>
<P>
As China deepens reform and accelerates its pace to build a
socialist market economic system, the collective sector has become
an inseparable force of the national economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The collective economy plays an important role in developing
production, making the market more prosperous, creating job
opportunities, improving people's living standards, and
maintaining social stability," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
"To check the asset value and capital stock of the urban
collective enterprises also amounts to a large-scale,
comprehensive survey of China's national conditions and strength,"
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
China launched a pilot program to ascertain the assets and
capital stock of urban collective enterprises last year, covering
13,000 such enterprises in 226 cities and prefectures nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Chen Qingtai, vice-minister of the State Commission of Economy
and Trade, said that expanding the program will be helpful to
standardizing the property rights relationship of the collective
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Li Yonggui, a chief economist of the State Administration of
Taxation, said that the latest effort is of real significance to
cultivating new tax resources and to raising the tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
Official records show that China had 495,000 urban-based
collective enterprises at the end of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
