<HEADLINE> Dhaka Urges Delhi to Maintain Ganges Water Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
called on New Delhi to maintain the flow of Ganges waters to the
country as per the provisions of the Indo-Bangladesh Water Treaty
signed in December 1996, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's concern was conveyed to Indian officials at the
just-concluded senior official level meeting on water on Monday,
said the sources.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the water flow to Bangladesh
of the river Ganges has continued being much below the agreed
water level stipulated in the treaty since this February.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Bangladesh officials failed to get any specific
assurance from the Indian officials about increasing the Ganges
flow to Bangladesh, particularly during the current critical
period of the dry season which began in early March.
</P>
<P>
The Indian officials said they will convey the concern and the
outcome of the meeting to their government.
</P>
<P>
The Indian side also mentioned that slow melting of Himalayan
ice and scarce rainfall had caused drop in the water level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
