<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Million Tanzanians Face Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa said about 4 million Tanzanians are facing food
shortage, needing some 138,765 tons of cereals and legumes to
sustain them in the next five months.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa said this in his speech broadcast live by
Radio Tanzania Dar es Salaam (RTD) on Monday, adding that the
government has so far spent some 2.83 million U.S. dollars on
easing the water shortage in Dar es Salaam, buying and
distributing relief food to famine hit areas.
</P>
<P>
"In the spirit of truth and transparency, I would like the
public to realize that this year's drought which has caused food
and water shortage will cost the government dearly," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This will imply diversion of funds which were initially
earmarked for development and social services," he added.
</P>
<P>
He further said that the government was striving to ensure
that relief supplies reached all the most hit areas, citing them as
Arusha, Coast, Dodoma, Kilimanjaro, Lindi, Mara, Mwanza,
Shinyanga, Singida, Tabora and Tanga regions.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the public to use food sparingly, saying a
joint evaluation by the Tanzanian government, the World Food
Programme (WFP), the Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) and the
U.S. aid agency USAID, showed that the situation was grave.
</P>
<P>
He told the nation that WFP has already shown interest of
giving Tanzania 11,000 tons of food, adding that it has so far
given the country 500 tons which have been distributed in Arusha
and Lindi regions.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa also appealed for relief supplies from the
public, religious organisations and various companies for flood
victims in Lindi Region of eastern Tanzania where 59 people have
so far died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
