<HEADLINE> Poverty Alleviation Key to Peace in Nigeria: Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Poverty and rural development are
key to future progress and stability in Nigeria, Chairman of the
Vision 2010 Committee of Nigeria Ernest Shonekan said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of a workshop of the committee on the
subject in Abuja, the former head of the interim government of
Nigeria warned that poverty is spreading in Nigeria and could
threaten the peace and stability of the nation.
</P>
<P>
He deplored the failure of all previous rural development
programs and called for a new one to be evolved.
</P>
<P>
About 62 percent of Nigeria's estimated 102 million population
now live in rural areas. In 1991, Nigeria was announced to be the
13th poorest country in the world by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to Shonekan, the level of poverty "has been rising
in leaps and bounds".
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the workshop, Dr. Foluso Okunmadewa of the
World Bank urged the Nigerian government to make "a firm
commitment to poverty reduction by making it the core element of
the development strategy."
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Minister of National Planning Ayp Ogunlade said
frequent policy changes has been responsible for perpetuation of
poverty in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
