<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Overseas Aid Falls Sharply in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Japan's official development aid
(ODA) fell 35 percent from 1995 to about 9.6 billion U.S. dollars
in 1996, the first since 1989 that its ODA in dollars terms
dropped from the previous year's level.
</P>
<P>
The sharp drop resulted from a 15-yen plunge in the exchange
rate of the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Foreign Ministry fears that the drop may make
Japan lose its position as the world's leading ODA donor country,
which it has enjoyed for five consecutive years up to 1995.
</P>
<P>
Japan's ODA kept growing in the early 1990s thanks to the
appreciation of the yen against the dollar, even though the amount
in terms of yen did not increase much.
</P>
<P>
Japan's ODA peaked at about 14.7 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
