<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Investigate Illegal Immigration Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan immigration officer has
said that he would send his officers to investigate an illegal
immigration ring which brings into Kenya hundreds of expatriates
every year, the East African Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper said Coast Province Immigration Officer
Zacchaecus Mboya had ordered for full details of the expatriate
contingent in the province.
</P>
<P>
The local paper today exposed powerful Italian tycoons
operating a Mafia-style tax evasion, thus denying Kenyan economy
millions of Dollars in revenue.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the illegal aliens enter the country
disguided as tourists, but were quickly given jobs in a myriad of
Italian-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the aliens have no bank accounts in
the country, nor the mandatory personal identification number for
any employed person.
</P>
<P>
The syndicate's operations are centered on the Kenya's North
Coast tourist resort towns of Watamu, Malindi and Mambrui, and
the expatriates are mainly employed at Italian-owned holiday
villas, cottages and hotels.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that they were flown in by airlines operated
by the same companies running the hotels.
</P>
<P>
The paper got a list of 300 illegal Italian expatriates from
two of the hotels involved in the ring, who are rotated every
three months to avoid their illegal employment.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Italian expatriates earn a basic salary of between
600 and 800 U.S. Dollars a month which is banked directly back
home in Italy, it added.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Revenue Authority Commissioner-General Yussuf Nzibo
confirmed that his office had received reports of organized tax
evasion by foreigners in the North Coast resorts.
</P>
<P>
"I get a lot of these reports and I have passed them on to the
Commissioner of Income Tax to investigate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Boniface Munyao, Deputy Secretary-General of the Central
Organization of Trade Unions, said that "we want the government
to check this and deport the Italians involved because they are
depriving Kenyans of their right to employment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
