<HEADLINE> Beijing to Use Lead-Free Gasoline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will lead China's use of
lead-free gasoline to reduce air pollution in the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to a municipal plan, Beijing will distribute
lead-free gasoline at more than 300 filling stations in eight
urban districts beginning July 1.
</P>
<P>
By January 1, 1998, lead-free petrol will be used all across
the municipality.
</P>
<P>
China's other four large cities, Shanghai, Tianjin, Guangzhou
and Shenzhen, will gradually adopt similar measures.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the output of lead-free petrol accounted
for 60 percent of the country's total. That figure is expected to
rise to 80 percent by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The switch from leaded gasoline to unleaded gasoline is part of
the nationwide drive to fight against air pollution, said the
local government.
</P>
<P>
The country is also speeding up research to produce catalytic
converters for motor vehicles to ensure cleaner exhaust emissions,
according to the Ministry of Machinery.
</P>
<P>
China's annual automobile output is some 1.4 million, that of
other motor vehicles reaches over 10 million. There are about 10
million automobiles in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
