<HEADLINE> South Korea Hits Monthly Record of Car Output in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's auto production hit a
monthly record in March, said a report of Korea's Automobile
Manufacturers Association (KAMA) released today.
</P>
<P>
Despite a sluggish domestic auto market this year, the total
production of seven carmakers stood at 271,801 units in March, up
8.6 percent from the same month last year, KAMA's preliminary
figures said.
</P>
<P>
The record production brought the total car output in the first
quarter to 632,481 units, 10 percent less than that in the same
period last year, due mainly to labor strikes early this year.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Motor topped the other carmakers by rolling out 120,623
units in March, up 28.9 percent from the previous month and 12.2
percent from March last year. Kia Motor made 67,240 units last
month, up 21.6 percent from February and 0.5 percent from March
last year.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter's sales of 539,368 units fell 17.7 percent
from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Slow auto sales are likely to result in an oversupply of cars,
putting a further burden on carmakers.
</P>
<P>
According to KAMA and Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy,
South Korea's car production capacity will be 3.953 million units
this year. However, due to the inventory stockpile, only 3 million
will be actually produced, at an average operation ratio of 75.9
percent, lower than 80.2 percent last year, industry sources
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
