<HEADLINE> Tanzania Gets Grants For Malaria Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Orgnisation (WHO) has allocated 600,000 U.S. dollars to Tanzania
under a 9-million-dollar malaria control scheme involving 21
African countries.
</P>
<P>
WHO country representative Dr. Dirk Warning made this
disclosure when speaking at the climax of celebrations to mark
the World Health Day here on Monday, saying the money would be
used to support the four-year action plan of the National Malaria
Control Program launched on April 7 this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the action plan (1997-2000) outlines how Tanzania and
WHO would jointly renew the fight against malaria in Tanzania and
reduce the impact of the disease drastically before the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that malaria was a public health problem in many
countries in the world, threatening about 40 percent of the
world's population and that 90 per cent of the affected people
live in Sub-Sahara Africa.
</P>
<P>
Warning further said malaria also has a lot of economic
implications in Tanzania in which about 100,000 out of over 15
million affected people die of the diseases annually, adding that
Tanzania was losing over 100 million U.S. Dollars annually due to
malaria treatment and management.
</P>
<P>
He said this year the World Health Day was being marked under
the theme "emerging and re-emerging communicable diseases" and
that in Tanzania the major communicable disease remained malaria.
enditem

