<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Wants Talks With Muslim Rebels on Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government expressed
the hope today that its low-level peace talks with the rebel Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) will open Wednesday as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Fortunato Abat, head of the government peace panel, told
reporters his technical committee will come to the scheduled venue
"with or without the MILF panel."
</P>
<P>
The technical committees of the government and the MNLF were
scheduled to meet on April 9-10 in Cotabato city in the southern
province of Maguindanao.
</P>
<P>
But a statement made by the MILF earlier this month said it
would boycott the talks until the March 16 bombing in Buldon,
Maguindanao, is resolved.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, 10 students and a teacher were killed when
a shell hit a school building in Buldon town, where the MILF and
the military were then exchanging gun fire. Both the MILF and the
military blamed each other for the killing.
</P>
<P>
The government has formed a team to look into the incident and
so far failed to determine which side should be responsible.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MNLF began exploratory talks in January,
but the talks have been on-and-off because of sporadic fighting
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF, a breakaway group of the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF), is currently the largest anti-government group in
the country, with an estimated membership of 12,000.
</P>
<P>
The group is opposed to the peace deal concluded last September
between the MNLF and the government and wanted its own peace talks
with the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
