<HEADLINE> Turkey to Import Natural Gas From Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish officials are making
contacts with Iraqi officials for purchase of its natural gas,
said a Turkish high-ranking official.
</P>
<P>
The Anatolia News Agency quoted Ugur Dogan, under-secretary of
the Energy and Natural Resources Ministry, as saying Monday that
Turkey has made "several contacts" with Iraq to specify the
quantity of the purchase and the building of a gas pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid said in Baghdad last
week that an agreement for the deal would be signed in July.
</P>
<P>
Rashid added that steps would also be taken in building the
300-kilometer pipeline between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Minister of Energy and Natural Resources Recai Kutan
was to visit Iraq later this month to discuss the preliminary
studies concerning this project.
</P>
<P>
Kutan has said that Turkey would need 27 billion cubic meters
of natural gas by the year 2000, a considerable increase from the
current 8 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-eight percent of Turkey's oil needs are imported. 
</P>
