<HEADLINE> World Shipping Tycoons to Meet in Istanbul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The world's leading shipping
magnates will meet in Turkey's largest city of Istanbul between
June 2 and 4 for the 52nd annual conference of the Baltic
International Maritime Council (BIMCO).
</P>
<P>
Esref Cerrahoglu, a leading Turkish ship-owner and also BIMCO
executive, said Monday that some 1,000 delegates from 108
countries will participate in the Istanbul meeting, which will
focus on such issues as shipping tonnage supply, safety and
freedom of the seas as well as navigation on the Bosporus.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, as one of most rapidly growing shipping countries, has
the world's 17th largest merchant fleet, with 132 members in its
maritime council.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the Turkish merchant fleet tonnage
has increased by 29 percent since 1994 to 10.9 million tons by the
end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
With over 2,600 members, the Copenhagen-based BIMCO controls
12,000 ships, accounting for 70 percent of the 722.5 million tons
of the world's merchant fleet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
