<HEADLINE> China to Spend 260 Billion Yuan in Major Chemical Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- China will invest 260 billion yuan
in building 470 large and medium-sized chemical projects over the
next few years to meet the country's demand for chemical
industrial products.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national meeting on chemical industrial
construction that opened here today, Gu Xiulian, minister of the
Chemical Industry, said that some 400 of the 470 projects will be
launched during the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000). In
1996 alone, construction of 30 of the projects was approved by
the central government.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on departments to step up feasibility
studies of the projects to ensure their quality. She emphasized
the necessity of greater use of sophisticated
domestically-developed or -made technologies and equipment to
improve investment efficiency of different projects.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five-Year Plan period, China will finish seven
major key task programs including complete sets of equipment for
making chemical fertilizers, with natural gas and coal as raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, China added new capacities to produce 6.64
million tons of synthetic ammonia, a rise of 26.2 percent over
that for the 1986-1990 period; 7.14 million tons of chemical
fertilizers, up 30.8 percent; 7.9 million tons of sulfur and
phosphorus, up 35 percent, according to Gu.
</P>
<P>
The country was also blessed with an increased production of
4.41 million tons of urea and high-concentration phosphate
fertilizer; and 8.82 million kg of grain during the 1996-90
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
