<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Government Opposed to Court Decision of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's Attorney General
Barrister Nabi said today that the government is opposed to the
High Court's decision of releasing four opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
A two-member High Court division bench Monday ordered the
release of four opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP)
leaders, who were detained under Special Powers Act from March 20.
</P>
<P>
In an unprecedented order, the High Court bench also directed
the government to pay compensatory cost of 100,000 taka (about
2500 U.S. dollars) to each of them for political victimization.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that former minister Khandaker Hossain,
former state minister Abdul Mannan and former mayor Mirza Abbas
have got free from Dhaka Central Jail last night.
</P>
<P>
Another BNP leader, former state minister Gayeshwar Roy, was,
however, not released as there has been another case pending
against him.
</P>
<P>
Denouncing the High Court's decision, Attorney General Nabi
said that so far he could recollect for first time in the history
of Bangladesh judiciary, the high court had ordered the government
to pay compensation in the judgment.  
</P>
