<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Ethnic Region Burgeoning into Granary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 8 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, long plagued by grain shortage, has not only
become self-sufficient but begun to export its grains to other
places.
</P>
<P>
The region produced a record grain output of 15.35 billion kg
last year, up 45.5 percent over the previous year, more than its
planned target of 14.5 billion kg by the end of the century, said
officials with the provincial Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
Its per-capita grain output was 667 kg, ranking first among the
provinces and regions. This enables the region to feed its 23
million population and have four billion kilograms for export
annually.
</P>
<P>
The region, inhabited by 50 ethnic groups, has more than 5.5
million ha of farmland. The per-capita share of land is three
times the national average. But the region used to live on resold
grains from elsewhere, shipping in 900 million kilograms annually.
</P>
<P>
The situation didn't change until 1992, when the region yielded
more than 10 billion kg of grain, ensuring adequate food for its
residents.
</P>
<P>
Agro-science is attributed to grain increases. New technologies
like plastic sheeting, seed coating, and desert rice have greatly
promoted agricultural productivity. Science and technology are
said to contribute 34 percent to agricultural growth.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1990, the region aroused 10,000 scientists and
technicians annually to help peasants farming, setting up
agro-science pilot projects in 100 townships, spreading
standardized farming techniques to 1.3 million ha, and training
two million farmers.
</P>
<P>
While its 40 agriculture-related colleges and institutes and
more than 40,000 agronomists are doing their best to ensure
successful harvests, the autonomous regional government spares no
effort to invest in agricultural production, and sets aside 10
percent of the increased revenue for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the region put 1.03 billion yuan into agricultural
development last year, a rise of 14.4 percent, and will invest
another four billion yuan by the year 2000 to improve medium- and
low-yield farmland, open up arable wasteland, and institute
agriculture support systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
