<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Wildlife Species Discovered in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Scientific researchers have
discovered new wildlife species in the 11,000-hectare triple
canopied rain forests in the Philippines' Subic Bay, an official
from the bay authority said today.
</P>
<P>
An on-going research showed that the well-preserved forests in
Subic Bay have yielded a bat about the size of a small finger and
two individual rodents belonging to two genera, said Richard
Gordon, chairman of the Subic Bay Metropolitan Authority.
</P>
<P>
These findings are the result of the eight-month old
Biodiversity Project being sponsored by the Department of Science
and Technology and the Philippine Council for Agriculture,
Forestry, Natural Resources Research and Development.
</P>
<P>
The bats, which belong to the Tylonyoteris Pachypus or Lesser
Flat-headed Bats, are about 60 to 62 millimeter long. They were
found in a relatively dense vegetation consisting of the
predominant bamboo species identified as Schizostachyum Lumapao.
</P>
<P>
The rodents were recently found by another scientific team. One
of the two rodents, belonging to Chrotomys, was described as a new
record of wildlife while the other one was said to belong to the
Phloemys Pallidus, may even belong to a new species.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Perry Ong, leader of the project, said both of the rodents
are being kept at the Institute of Biology of the University of
the Philippines for further verification and study.
</P>
<P>
He added that they are preparing a full research report to be
presented to the workshop of the Wildlife Conservation Society of
the Philippines on April 22-25.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
