<HEADLINE> Foreign Diplomats Asked to Keep off Kenya's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has told diplomats and other foreigners in the country to keep
off Kenya's internal affairs, the Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The president asked foreign friends of the country to desist
from telling Kenyans how to run their own affairs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at public rallies on Monday in Bomet District in
western Kenya, Moi said many countries in Africa had faced
numerous problems because of succumbing to external influences.
</P>
<P>
President Moi referred to some envoys' participation in the
National Convention on Constitutional Reform held by opposition
parties last week in Limuru near Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
"The convention claims that even diplomats were there to speak
on behalf of Wananchi (people). Among the diplomats were
Americans and Britons... who have the right to decide the fate of
others?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Moi stressed that it was wrong for the envoys to interfere
with the affairs of Kenyans by attending such conventions, adding
that "we have a right to live our own lives, the problems in
Rwanda and Zaire was started by outsiders like these ones."
</P>
