<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangpu Special Economic Zone Forging ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Yangpu Development Zone, in
northwest Hainan Province, has become China's largest
export-oriented bonded zone with an area of 30 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The zone and Shanghai's Pudong New Area are the two remaining
"special zones" in China in which foreign investors can still
enjoy preferential treatment in fields as import and export,
taxation, foreign exchange, and custom services.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiang Shangzhou, director of the Yangpu
Development Administration, conditions are ready for large-scale
construction.
</P>
<P>
To woo more overseas businessmen, Yangpu has invested heavily
in infrastructure. The developers have poured four billion HK
dollars into building a 315,000-kw power plant, a 43-km-long road
net, and a telecom network with 2,200 telephones lines, 150 mobile
phones, and paging services.
</P>
<P>
The Hainan provincial government has invested 2.2 billion yuan
in paving an expressway linking the zone with Haikou, the provincial
capital.
</P>
<P>
The state-funded Yangpu Harbor now has two berths for ships of
20,000 DWT and another berth for ships of 3,000 DWT. The three
berths have a combined handling capacity of one million tons of
freight a year.
</P>
<P>
The second-phase construction of the harbor will be due
soon. Upon completion, the harbor will add three new berths for
vessels of 20,000 DWT and increase its handling capacity to 2.5
million tons of freight a year.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiang, some 30-odd major projects with a total
investment of 100 billion yuan are underway or at the "final stage
of negotiations," ushering in a new wave of investment.
</P>
<P>
The State Planning Commission (SPC) has approved the
construction of China's largest chemical fertilizer plant in
Yangpu. The project, at the cost of 15.58 billion yuan, is set to
produce 900,000 tons of synthetic ammonia and 1.6 million tons of
carbamide annually upon completion.
</P>
<P>
Construction of a 1.3-billion-US-dollar pulp plant, also set in
the zone and funded by a foreign investor, is expected to be
approved by the SPC.
</P>
<P>
Executives from such multinational corporations, such as
Japan's Misushita, German's Siemens and BMW, and Daewoo from the
Republic of Korea, in recent years visited the zone and showed
interest in the area.
</P>
<P>
Jiang vowed to better the investment environment this year
by promulgating more regulations and efficient administration
to attract more overseas investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
