<HEADLINE> Diamond Giant De Beers Holds Talks With Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's diamond giant
De Beers asked Zairean rebel leader Laurent Kabila to protect its
staff and facilities in rebel-controlled eastern Zaire, De Beers
confirmed on Monday in a statement.
</P>
<P>
However, details of the contents or venue of the talks were
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
De Beers has trading offices in Zaire's diamond capital
Mbuji-Mayi, which is currently in the control of Kabila's
Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire.
</P>
<P>
It also has an office in Kisangani, Zaire's third largest city
which recently fell to the hands of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
De Beers has a contract to buy the products of the MIBA mine
at Mbuji-Mayi, which the Zairean government owned 80 percent
shares to.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's rebel forces has gained control of about one third of
Zaire's territory since the breakout of the civil war in October
last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, representatives of warring sides are currently in
South Africa for peace talks in an attempt to seek a lasting
solution to the civil war. 
