<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sci-Fi on Human Clone Wins Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- "Empire of Clones," a
science-fiction story was awarded the "Galaxy Prize" by "Science
Fiction World" magazine this month.
</P>
<P>
Published last April, the short story by Pan Haitian forecast a
disaster brought about by unrestricted clone technology in the
22nd century.
</P>
<P>
In the story, Earth is controlled by an empire whose citizens
are human clones. A cruel emperor produces millions of people
every year, using them as slaves and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Human nature is distorted, life absurd, and without rebellion.
</P>
<P>
The story's protagonist is not a clone, but one whose love is
destroyed by the cloning process.
</P>
<P>
Critics said that the technology described in the story is
similar to that which produced "Dolly" in Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Dolly", a sheep, was the first animal cloned with a cell
obtained from a mature animal's body.
</P>
<P>
The issue has aroused ethical debates throughout the world
since February this year. Many countries have vowed to ban the
cloning of human beings.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists suggested that measures be adopted to
prevent biological technology from becoming a weapon that might
destroy man.
</P>
<P>
Chen Minzhang, Minister of Public Health, said that China will
strictly ban human cloning to avoid dangerous technological,
social, and ethical consequences.
</P>
<P>
Pan is a student studying in the prestigious Qinghua
University, China's top college for sciences and engineering. He
is regarded as one of the most talented Sci-Fi writers of the new
generation.
</P>
<P>
"Science Fiction World" magazine, which gave the award, was
named as the "Best Sci-Fi Magazine" by the World Sci-Fi
Organization in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The magazine bestows prizes every April to ten authors who
created the best works in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Together with "The Empire of Clones", nine other short stories
have won the prizes. They touched issues like cyberspace, time
travel, and the exploration of the Mars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
