<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environmentalist Stops at Nothing in his Efforts (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The single most exciting thing for
Qu Geping, who has devoted 25 years of his life to environmental
protection in China, was when China closed 60,000 small factories
because of serious pollution problems, last year.
</P>
<P>
"In the history of mankind, no other country could do something
like that," he said, "The huge economic loss and social burden
caused by the move shows the tremendous determination of the
Chinese government to protect the environment."
</P>
<P>
Qu, who is a professor and chairman of the Environment and
Resource Protection Committee of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, told Xinhua that, during the Ninth
Five-Year Plan, a total of 450 billion yuan (56 billion US dollars)
is expected to be spent on environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
"The ratio of the GDP spent on environmental protection in
China will remain the highest among developing countries, and in
some provinces like Shandong, the proportion is expected to reach
or even exceed that of developed countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qu, 67, is regarded as a pioneer in China's environmental
protection endeavor, which started 25 years ago. He is still
hard at work in his office near the Great Hall of the People in
Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environmentalist Stops at Nothing in his Efforts (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Qu became the first Chinese representative to the UN
Environment Programme (UNEP), the first Chinese director of the
Environment Protection Bureau, the first Chinese winner of a top
UN environment protection prize, the first Chinese minister to work
with the UNEP on a book, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
He still remembers the situation 25 years ago, when the Chinese
government sent a delegation, himself included, to the UN
conference on environment in Stockholm in 1972.
</P>
<P>
"The UN conference on the environment actually opened a window
for China to see its environmental problems," he noted, "When
Premier Zhou Enlai heard our reports on the theme of the
conference, he said that immediate action should be taken to
control the already serious environmental problems."
</P>
<P>
"So, the year 1972 marked the starting point and a very
important milestone for China's environmental protection work," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
It was also the year that Qu started his career as both an
environmental protection official and an environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
He said that, after 1973, four national meetings on
environmental protection were held by the State Council, China's
highest administrative body, to attach greater importance to the
issue and increase awareness of environmental protection among the
public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environmentalist Stops at Nothing in his Efforts (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a leading official in charge of environment protection in a
country with 1.2 billion people and a rapidly growing economy, Qu
has long been one of the busiest officials in China.
</P>
<P>
He said that China should adopt the approach of "controlling
pollution while developing the economy" and not the western method
of "first causing pollution and then controlling it."
</P>
<P>
He has participated in formulating an environmental protection
policy with Chinese characteristics, putting forth the principle
that "whoever causes pollution must be held responsible for
controlling pollution." This has made him one of the first backers
of a market mechanism in China.
</P>
<P>
As a scholar, Qu is also the author of many books and articles,
some of them published abroad.
</P>
<P>
In his "Environmental Management in China," published by the
UNEP, he outlined his ideas about the environmental assessment
system, the environmental responsibility system, the fee
collection system for pollutants, and the quantitative management
system for urban environment cleaning.
</P>
<P>
According to a UNEP official, Qu "has developed the theory of
environment management," and "China has set a good example for all
developing countries to follow in protecting their environment."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the current environmental protection situation in
China, he said that, for historical and financial reasons, China
still faces tough environmental challenges, and painstaking
efforts should be made to halt the worsening trend in
environmental problems by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
But he also showed confidence in China ability to meet its
environmental protection goal: "With the attention of leaders at
all levels and the participation of all residents, China will
certainly be able to create a good living and ecological
environment by the year 2010." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0213 </DOCNO>
