<HEADLINE> Mexico's Export to Reach Over Hundred Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's export in 1997 is
projected to increase by 16 percent from a year earlier to 110
billion U.S. dollars, a bank report said today.
</P>
<P>
The report issued by the bank Bancomext said Mexico's import
will also increase by 20 percent to dramatically cut back its
trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
This export rate is lower than that of the previous two years
of 30 percent and 20 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 years, Mexico's non-petroleum export increased
444 percent making it the biggest exporter in the Latin American
region.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's share of the world market rose from 0.82 percent in
1986 to 1.12 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the exporting sector represented 28 percent and
importing sector 22.2 percent of Mexico's gross domestic product
(GDP), said the report. 
</P>
