<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONGKONG, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Video taping spectators at the
Mongkok Stadium is unnecessary and impractical, a senior Hong Kong
police officer said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Mongkok Divisional Commander, Chan Lik-kin, was responding
to an earlier suggestion put forward by Hong Kong Football
Association (HKFA) chairman Victor Hui Chun-fui.
</P>
<P>
Hui had said that filming the spectators would make it easier
for police to identify and arrest troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
"I personally don't think video tapes will do much to help.
The stadium is too big for our cameraman to cover at the
spectators. And you never know when and where a disturbance will
happen," Chan was quoted by today's English-language newspaper
South China Morning Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
A video tape will help if useful shots are obtained but the
cameraman would find it difficult to be on the spot whenever
trouble occurs, he said.
</P>
<P>
To make arrest, all police need are eyewitnesses, not video
tapes, he said.
</P>
<P>
The police handling of an ugly scene for Thursday's First
Division League match between Instant-Dict and Sing Tao at Mongkok
have been criticized and allegations were made that police took no
on-the-spot actions.
</P>
<P>
Missiles were seen being thrown to the families of Sing Tao's
expatriate players who had to flee from the attack believed to be
launched by supporters of the South China team. A Sing Tao
player's two-year-old daughter was nearly hit by a plastic water
bottle during the incident. Police were accused of not having
arrested the troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
Chan said police did take actions but no arrests were made.
"Instead, our police officers asked a few of those who started the
trouble to leave the stadium," he said. Once they left the site
the situation returned to normal, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
"Arrests were not always the best way to control crowds," Chan
said. But no arrests at the time did not mean that no actions had
been taken by police, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
