<HEADLINE> U.S. TV Industry to Poll Parents on Rating System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- America's TV industry is to ask
parents about the need for major changes to the three-month-old
rating system, Jack Valenti, the executive who oversaw its
creation, said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The industry would be talking to the nation's roughly 1,600 TV
stations to get parental feedback on the effectiveness of the
six-tier age-based ratings, Valenti, also the president of the
Motion Picture Association of America, told the National
Association of Broadcasters convention in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
But he wouldn't be drawn on what results would be required to
trigger major changes to the age-based ratings that went into
effect Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
The survey of more than 1000 parents, selected at random, will
start next month, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Studies carried out so far say parents want more detailed
reeffectiveness.
</P>
<P>
Ranging from "TV-G" for all audiences to "TV-MA," mature
audiences only, the voluntary ratings have been criticized by
lawmakers and children's advocacy groups for not providing parents
enough information about the sexual, violence and language content
of shows.
</P>
<P>
But broadcasters and basic cable networks that depend on
advertising as their main source of revenue fear they may lose
advertising if shows are flagged for sex and violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
