<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Popular Movement Day Marked in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand said today that Nepal has made big strides in terms
of the institutional development of democracy following two
general elections since 1990.
</P>
<P>
But the country's progress in the economic and other sectors
has not been commensurate with the people's aspirations, Chand
noted in a public message issued on the occasion of the Popular
Movement Day today.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has witnessed lower economic growth in recent years after
a multi-party parliamentary system was introduced in 1990, mainly
due to the frequent change of government, economic analysts here
said.
</P>
<P>
The political instability in the country, resulting from the
fact that no political party holds a single majority in the
powerful lower house of parliament, has led to the interruption of
the continuous implementation of economic policies and measures,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The country last month saw the fifth government since 1990
while Prime Minister Chand happened to be the last premier under
the partyless Panchayat legislature system.
</P>
<P>
Chand, a leader of the National Democratic Party (RPP) mainly
comprising former Panchayat legislators, managed to forge a ruling
coalition with the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist
Leninist, CPN-UML) in early March after the former government led
by the Nepali Congress (NC) party lost a confidence vote in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The two major forces leading the 1990 nationwide popular
movement which ushered in the multi-party parliamentary system,
the NC and the CPN-UML, have finally become arch rivals in
parliament with 88 and 90 MPs respectively in the 205-seat lower
house.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, various programs have been organized across Nepal
these days to mark the 1990 nationwide popular movement.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government decided to observe the Popular Movement
Day on every year's April 8 to commemorate the historic
announcement by King Birendra to abolish the partyless Panchayat
legislature and reinstate the parliamentary system seven years
ago.
</P>
<P>
In the southern Nepali town of Bhadrapur, over 850 political
activists, including those who had been put into prison due to
their involvement in the movement, were honored at a function held
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mass meetings and processions were also organized in other
major cities with the participation of students, local youths,
intellectuals, and political and social workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
