<HEADLINE> Singapore Investors Cut Back Equity Stake In US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Investors based in Singapore
sharply reduced their investment in equities in the United States
to a net 2.2 billion US dollars at the end of last year, down 60
percent from the record 5.58 billion US dollars as at the end of
1995.
</P>
<P>
According to a Business Times report today, the reduction came
despite a spurt of buying in the fourth quarter, when a net 1.3
billion US dollars of equities was bought against heavy net
divestment of 2.1 billion US dollars in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
In addition to equities, Singapore-based investors also bought
7.7 billion US dollars of US government treasuries in 1996, down
from 8.9 billion US dollars for 1995.
</P>
<P>
Singapore was the fourth biggest foreign buyers of US stock in
1996 while Britain topped the league with 4.1 billion US dollars.
British investors were also the biggest buyers of Treasury
securities, with a portfolio of 64.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The biggest Singapore investor is widely thought, as the report
said, to be the Government Investment Corporation (GIC). The GIC,
which normally does not reveal its investment, manages Singapore's
foreign reserves, estimated at 100 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
A sizable chunk of its portfolio investments is thought to be
in the United States, the Business Times said.
</P>
<P>
Other Singapore-based investors in the US securities, in
particular equities, include high net worth individuals from the
region, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
