<HEADLINE> Wheat Shortage in Pakistan Sparks Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The wheat flour crisis in
Pakistan has sparked violence in several major cities despite
assurances from the government.
</P>
<P>
Violence by protesters demanding adequate flour supply was
reported Monday from various parts of North West Frontier Province
and Punjab Province as mobs attacked the flour mills and the
special outlets used for the sale of flour.
</P>
<P>
Protest rallies were also held Monday in Rawalpindi, the sister
city of Islamabad, where people bitterly criticized the government
for not making arrangements for smooth supply of the most
essential commodity.
</P>
<P>
Incidents of looting of flour bags and blocking of roads also
took place on Sunday in Lahore, the capital city of central Punjab
Province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, despite the involvement of district administration
in the distribution network and supervision of flour mills,
black-marketing of flour continued.
</P>
<P>
The government has promised to take all possible measures to
overcome the flour shortage.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif announced Monday
that transportation of imported wheat from the Karachi port was on
a "war-footing" to alleviate shortages in the country.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman blamed unidentified "vested interests" for
creating an "artificial" shortage of flour, which has lasted more
than a month.
</P>
<P>
A judicial inquiry into the crisis would be conducted and those
responsible would "not be spared", he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly was tangled in a prolonged discussion on
Monday on the country-wide wheat crisis after members sounded
ominous warnings to the government that the situation could get
out of control.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the situation might improve over the next
few days when the imported wheat will reach the four mills and
adequate supply of flour will start.  
</P>
</TEXT>
