<HEADLINE> Iran Sues German Firms for Chemical Supply to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran today asked representatives of
24 German firms and some German government officials to appear in
an Iranian court on charges of chemical weapons supply to Iraq
during the Iran-Iraq war from 1980 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by a spokesman of the Iranian
judicial authorities following a meeting of judicial officials in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Iran had concrete evidences in proof of
Germany's supply of chemical weapons to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The evidences included pictures, films and testimony given by
German technicians who had cooperated with the Iraqi Army in
deploying the chemical weapons, he added.
</P>
<P>
The relatives of the Iranian victims and the disabled by the
chemical weapons demanded compensation and punishment of those
German chemical weapon exporters and a number of German officials
who permitted the export of chemical weapons to Iraq, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The claims by the families of the victims have been studied
and the crime and damage happened inside the Iranian territory,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Without naming the 24 German firms, the spokesman said that
those names had already been listed in the law suit, and the third
Tehran General court had been authorized to handle the case.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Iran had accused 84 German companies, including
Toysen, Zigma and Hebergerbau, of supplying chemical weapons to
Iraq during the war.
</P>
<P>
Abdollah Mazandarani, Iranian Secretary General of the
Association for Helping Victims of Iraq's Chemical Warfare, said
that some 25,000 Iranians had been killed and 65,000 others
injured by chemical bombs in the war.
</P>
<P>
Most of the chemical weapons delivered to Iraq had been
disguised as pesticides, he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the Iranian charges against the German
firms and some officials might be a retaliation against a German
court, which had accused some Iranian leaders of ordering to kill
three Iranian Kurdish dissident leaders and their interpreter in
Berlin in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
