<HEADLINE> Indian Airlines Floats Global Tender to Sell Airbus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- As part of its 35 billion rupees
(985.92 million us dollars) fleet renewal program, the Indian
Airlines (IA) has floated a global tender for the sale of three
Airbus A-300 aircraft in its fold, IA sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The IA currently has 10 Airbus A-300 planes in its fleet and it
plans to phase out all of them in the next two or three years. The
three planes up for sale are above 20 years in age and cannot be
operated in India under Directorate General of Civil Aviation
(DGCA) guidelines.
</P>
<P>
"The replacement of the IA's fleet with newer planes is going
to be on top of the agenda. Out of the 55 aircraft with the IA, 22
are due for replacement," said P.J. Crasta, deputy managing
director of IA.
</P>
<P>
"The IA will have to buy new planes and have a fleet strength
of 70-75 aircraft by the year 2002 to enable us to maintain our
market share," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IA has floated a global tender to buy five Airbus aircraft
on dry lease as a first step.  
</P>
</TEXT>
