<HEADLINE> China, Czech Republic to Further Develop Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China and the Czech Republic will
further develop political and economic relations, said visiting
Chinese Vice Premier Wu Bangguo here today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Czech newspapers Pravo (Right) and
Hospodarske Noviny (Economic News), Wu said, "China attaches great
importance to the development of its relations with the Czech
Republic."
</P>
<P>
"China is willing to maintain the long-term friendship and
mutually beneficial cooperation between the two countries on the
basis of mutual respect, equality and mutual benefit, and
non-interference in each other's internal affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries have potentially complementary economies,
and the ties will develop in a satisfactory way with the joint
efforts of the two sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the issue of China's joining the World Trade
Organization (WTO), Wu said that the rapid growth in China's
foreign trade as a result of its policy of reform had paved the
way for China to join the WTO.
</P>
<P>
He said China's joining of the WTO serves the interest of both
China and the world at large, as both sides need each other.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the human rights issue, the Chinese vice premier
said that China had made great achievements in protection of human
rights and freedom.
</P>
<P>
China has always maintained that countries should conduct
dialogues and discussions on the human rights issue on the basis of
equality and mutual respect, Wu added.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Wu held talks respectively with Czech
Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus, Chairman of the Deputies Chamber
(lower house) Milos Zeman and Vice Prime Minister and Foreign
Minister Josef Zielenice.
</P>
<P>
Wu, who arrived in the Czech Republic on April 3 after visiting
Ukraine and Belarus, will also go to Finland and Sweden to
continue his five-nation Europe tour, which began on March 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
