<HEADLINE> Ukraine Sacks Deputy Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
today dismissed Deputy Prime Minister Viktor Pinzenik, widely
regarded as the architect of the country's economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Pinzenik, who has been in charge of Ukraine's reform program
since 1994, tendered his resignation last Wednesday, accusing the
government and parliament of dragging their heels on approving
the 1997 budget and tax changes needed to underpin the spending
plans.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today after Kuchma's announcement,
Pinzenik said the Ukranian authorities lacked the political will
to continue the reforms.
</P>
<P>
Pinzenik, 42, took much of the credit for the successful
introduction of the new currency hryvnia last year, and his tough
policies helped bring inflation down to 39.7 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister, seen as a Western-style reformer,
has constantly complained in the past months about low foreign
investment and ineffective reforms.
</P>
<P>
And he reportedly became frustrated at delays in passing the
budget which would have paved the way for Ukaine to receive a 2.5
billion to 3 billion U.S.-dollar loan from the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Pinzenik's exit from the government is the latest in a
string of sackings and departures in the cabinet over the last few
days.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma has sacked ministers of the economy, finance, energy and
agriculture as he was unhappy about the state of the economy which
has been in crisis since independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here expect Prime Minister Pavel Lazarenko to submit
his plans for a cabinet reshuffle to the Ukrainian parliament on
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
