<HEADLINE> Job Hunt A Big Lesson For College Graduates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Large numbers of college graduates
in China are this year set to learn the toughest lesson of all --
the lesson of life, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The number of Chinese students winning degrees this year means
they have to face fiercer job competition in the summer compared
with last year, officials at the State Education Commission said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 900,000 college students -- 849,000 college students
and nearly 50,000 students with master or doctorate degrees, will
graduate in July, compared with about 860,000 who graduated last
year, according to the commission.
</P>
<P>
Generally, the demand for graduates equals supply, but to
different students things are not the same, said a commission
official yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The specialties in demand are engineering, medicine,
pharmacology and teacher-training, while the students of
literature, history, agriculture, forestry, finance and economics
and some natural sciences will find it harder to secure
satisfactory jobs.
</P>
<P>
Employers want graduates with a higher education background,
ability and the membership of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
Graduate students are the most popular in the job market this
year, while the demand for two or three-year-college students have
been reduced by half, a situation worse than last year. The demand
for undergraduates is in the middle, according to commission
sources.
</P>
<P>
The source said that there is a great demand for graduate
students and students of key universities, in job assignment,
especially students from prestigious universities.
</P>
<P>
A teacher in charge of the job assignments at Beijing's Qinghua
University said that up to now, most graduates of Qinghua
University have found jobs.
</P>
<P>
Except for the students who are going on to study in graduate
schools and those who plan to go abroad at their own expenses,
only about 40 percent of graduates of Qinghua University plan to
find jobs this summer.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing Normal University, every student who wants to be a
teacher has two jobs to choose from on average, more opportunities
than the students of non-teacher-training specialities.
</P>
<P>
Because the status of teachers and income have been greatly
improved in recent years, more students of non-teachers'
universities are happy to work as teachers.
</P>
<P>
Higher degree means more job opportunities, but the college
graduates are urged to lower their job expectants and are
encouraged to find jobs in medium-sized and small cities and
inland regions where there is an urgent need for college
graduates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
