<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks in Indonesia Required to Lend to Small </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia, the central bank,
has made it compulsory for joint ventures and foreign banks to
participate in the development of small businesses in the country
by lending them money.
</P>
<P>
"This policy was taken in line with the provisions of the World
Trade Organization, which does not want discriminative approaches
to local and foreign banks," the bank's director for credit
Mukhlis Rasyid said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the bank said joint ventures and foreign banks in
Indonesia did not have to meet any minimum lending requirement to
small businesses, but they must allocate 50 percent of their
lending as export credit.
</P>
<P>
With the new policy, they now must allocate at least 12.5
percent of this calendar year's increase in their outstanding
rupiah and foreign exchange credit to small businesses, Mukhlis
said.
</P>
<P>
Next year, they will have to give at least 17.5 percent of
their total credit expansion to small businesses. The quota will
rise to 22.5 percent in 1999, he added.
</P>
<P>
But foreign banks will no longer have to give 50 percent of
their credit as export credit. Instead they must lend 80 percent
of their offshore borrowings as export credit.
</P>
<P>
According to the new ruling, banks that can not meet the set
lending ratio will have to pay two percent of the difference to
Bank Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, banks which exceed the mandatory small-business
lending ratio up to 30 percent will get 0.5 percent of the excess.
</P>
<P>
Banks with small business lending ratio of between 30 percent
to 40 percent will get one percent while those with over 40
percent ratio will get 1.5 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
