<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Closer Cooperation with Palestine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan today
called for a closer cooperation between Jordan and Palestine to
promote the Middle East peace process and for the benefit of the
two countries, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Coordination between Jordan and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) should materialize into concrete political and
economic steps that serve the vital interests of both peoples,
Hassan said during a meeting with senior PNA official Mohamoud
Abbas at the Royal Court.
</P>
<P>
Such cooperation could help Palestinian negotiators in the
peace talks and regain the legitimate and inalienable rights of
the Palestinian people, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hassan also called for bilateral efforts in shaping
comprehensive security, including social and economic security, in
the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Abbas said the PNA was keen on ending the tension caused by the
stalled talks with the Israeli government and resuming the peace
talks with Israel, he added.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Palestinian and Jordanian businessman announced a
plan to raise a 100-million-U.S.-dollar fund for investment in
Arabian East Jerusalem in a bid to counter Israeli settlement
activities in the city. This was the latest act of economic
coordination between Jordan and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace has stopped since Israel started
building a new Jewish housing project in East Jerusalem last
month. The project has also triggered violence in the Palestinian
self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein, recuperating from cancer treatment at Mayo
Hospital in the United States, met Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu earlier today to discuss the latest developments in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is in the United States for talks with President Bill
Clinton which will include the final status of the disputed city
of Jerusalem and the controversial housing project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
