<HEADLINE> Lebanon Calls for Russian Help in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Lebanese Prime Minister
Rafik Al Hariri today called on Russia to help revive Middle East
peace negotiations which have stalled over Israel's building of a
new Jewish housing settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Hariri told reporters after a meeting with Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov that Israel should observe the
resolutions of the U.N. Security Council and adhere to the
principle of land for peace which was agreed at Middle East Peace
Conference in Madrid in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said Russia would put forward proposals on the basis
of the Madrid principle. He stressed that if Israeli conflicts
with Lebanon, Syria and Palestine can't be resolved, peace
throughout the Middle East will be difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
Hariri is in Moscow on a three-day visit to boost trade and
economic ties between the two countries. But with Russia a
co-sponsor with the United States of the peace process and seeking
to play a larger role in the talks, Hariri has called for Russian
support to restart Israeli-Palestinian dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The talks stopped after Israel broke ground for a new
6,500-home Jewish settlement last month on Har Homa in disputed
East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
