<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptians Vote in Calm Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Voting for municipal councils all
over Egypt went on quietly today, with some 5,000 heavily-guarded
polling stations operating smoothly.
</P>
<P>
About 58,000 candidates were running for the 47,682 seats on
local councils in Egypt's 26 provinces, the Egyptian MENA news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The ruling National Democratic Party headed by President Hosni
Mubarak is expected to net a lop-sided victory since the
opposition parties have failed to field candidates in many areas
in the vote for a five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Official results will not be available until Tuesday, but the
ruling party reportedly won all 1,013 seats by default in the
Ismailiya province, about 120 kilometers northeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Hassan al-Alfy said that no major violence
occurred at polling stations and no police intervention was
observed in the voting.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 33 people were killed in two rounds of the last
parliamentary elections in November and December 1995.
</P>
<P>
Alfy estimated the turnout at 40 percent in Cairo and
Alexandria, the country's biggest and second largest
cities. Twenty million of Egypt's 62 million people are eligible
to vote.
</P>
<P>
One main opposition party, the Wafd, boycotted the vote while
other opposition parties found it hard to get candidates to run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
