<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cepal Advocates Economic Growth With Justice To Erradicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As for jobs and salaries, the Cepal said that during this
decade, most of the jobs being generated correspond to the
informal sector.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates made by the International Labor
Organization (ILO), 84 out of every 100 new jobs created between
1990 and 1995 corresponded to the informal sector, the sector to
which 56 percent of all those who have jobs belong.
</P>
<P>
It added that in 1995 the real minimum wage in 13 of the 17
Latin American and Caribbean countries that supplied information
was below the 1980 level.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, in 7 of the 11 countries that provided
information about increases in social spending, the levels reached
surpassed those at the beginning of the eighties. Public spending
on social prgrams with respect to the GDP increased an average of
1.8 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The housing deficit in the region has reached 50 million
units. This figure includes both the need to build new housing and
the need to rehabilitate their houses. The deficit is growing by
2.7 million houses per year.
</P>
<P>
Sixty of every 100 households in the region have adequate
housing, 22 require improvements and 18 need new housing or the
rebuilding of the houses it occupies.
</P>
<P>
The Cepal mentioned that "in order to advance in a more
efficient way in the compliance of the commitments made at the
Social Summit, an integrated focus of the economic and social
policies is required." 
</P>
</TEXT>
