<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (9-10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After 1997, the Hong Kong SAR will have greater autonomous
powers than not only the country's ethnic minority autonomous
regions but also members of federal states.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, for example, no individual states enjoy
such autonomous powers as the following to be enjoyed by Hong
Kong: the formulation and implementation of independent economic,
trade and tariff policies, independence in customs affairs,
independence in finances, the right to issue its own currency, the
status of a separate customs territory, and independent entry and
exit controls, not to say independent judicial power, including
that of final adjudication, as well as the right to handle external
affairs independently.
</P>
<P>
In fact, in administrative and economic areas and in
legislative and judicial systems, no local government of any other
country in the world and no member of any federal state enjoy such
numerous and extensive autonomous powers as the Hong Kong SAR will
have.
</P>
<P>
Question: What does "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong"
mean? Why should patriotic Hong Kong people form the main
governing body of Hong Kong?
</P>
<P>
Answer: It means that Hong Kong will be administered
independently by the local people. For more than 100 years of
British rule, Hong Kong has been under the autocratic rule of
governors appointed by the British Crown.
</P>
<P>
After 1997, the Chinese government, in accordance with the
principle of "one country, two systems," will implement the policy
of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong." This shows the central
government's deep trust in the six million Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
When Deng Xiaoping met with some Hong Kong visitors in June
1984, he said: "There have to be some requirements and standards
for Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong. That is, patriots should
form the main body of administrators."
</P>
<P>
"Who are patriots? They are people who respect their own
nation, sincerely support the motherland's resumption of
sovereignty over Hong Kong and do not harm Hong Kong's prosperity
and stability."
</P>
<P>
It is a natural requirement of the "one country, two systems"
policy that patriots should form the main body of Hong Kong's
administrators. This is because it is part of China and the great
majority of Hong Kong residents are Chinese.
</P>
<P>
If administrators do not love their country and Hong Kong, how
can they do a good job? Implementation of the "one country, two
systems" policy will not be possible, nor can the long-term
prosperity and stability of Hong Kong be maintained unless Hong
Kong is administered by a local government staffed mainly by
patriots.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0259 </DOCNO>
