<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cepal Advocates Economic Growth With Justic To Erradicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The organization said that the fundamental objective of the
meeting is to contribute to a reflection on how to overcome
poverty, the generation of productive jobs and social integration,
the 3 issues dealt with at the World Summit on Social Development
that was held in Copenhague, Denmark in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Cepal is analyzing regional socio-economic evolution in the
90s and is proposing a set of political options oriented to the
simultaneous achievement of economic growth and fair distribution,
with priority also given to the efficacy and efficiency in matters
of social policy.
</P>
<P>
In its study, the Cepal said that the growth rates of the gross
domestic product (GDP) in Latin America and the Caribbean "have
been moderate (3 percent per year between 1990-1996), inferior to
the historical performance of 5.5 percent per year between 1945
and 1980 and to the levels believed by the Cepal to be necessary
to tackle technological and social gaps.
</P>
<P>
The important accumulation of social gaps generated during the
economic crisis of the eighties are diminishing slowly, especially
in 3 interelated aspects: the job situation, the poverty rate and
the actual exclusion.
</P>
<P>
The Cepal emphasized that "both the macroeconomic balances as
well as the way to reach them are crucial for an accelerated and
more equitable growth.
</P>
<P>
"Together with reducing the inflation rate and strengthening
the fiscal equilibrium, it is also necessary to attain a
sustainable deficit in current accounts, a level of internal
savings in accordance with the investment process, an adequate
exchange rate level and a level of internal spending compatible
with sustainable uses of the productive capacity, he added.
</P>
<P>
The lack of advance against poverty in the region continues to
be associated to the lack of economic growth, to its weak impact
on the labor market and a virtual stagnation in the labor
productivity average, a vital aspect if international
competitiveness is to be improved and if sustainable rates of
growth are to be reached, said the Cepal. (to be continued)
