<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Defense Agency chief Fumio
Kyuma and U.S. defense secretary william Cohen agreed today to
maintain the current level of U.S.troops in Japan, Kyodo news
service quoted defense agency officials as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The two defense chiefs reached the agreement in talks held in
Tokyo this evening.
</P>
<P>
Japan hosts 47,000 of the 100,000 U.S. troops deployed in East
Asia, of which, about 27,000 stationed in Japan's island Okinawa
Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
The two defense chiefs also agreed that the two countries will
draw up an interim report in May reviewing the 1978 guidelines on
Japan-U.S.defense cooperation, agency official said.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed the two countries will continue a joint study
of the Theater Missile Defense system (TMD), a regional
anti-missile defense system Japan has been studying for about two
years so as to decide whether or not to participate, the officials
were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived in Tokyo earlier in the day for a three-day visit
to Japan to have talks with Japanese leaders on the U.S. military
presence in Okinawa and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
