<HEADLINE> More Help for Hard-up Students in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Hard-up Beijing college students
will be offered more helping hands, all bearing money, to enable
them to finish their studies, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
About 13,000 students are living on less than 14 US dollars a
month in the capital, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
A special fund will be set up this year for poor students
attending the 67 colleges and universities in Beijing, the Beijing
Education Administration (BEA) announced yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The BEA also announced that a scholarship foundation will be
established to provide financing to financially burdened students
who volunteer to work in remote and poverty-stricken areas after
graduation.
</P>
<P>
The administration will also formulate regulations concerning
loan management to encourage students to make efficient use of
borrowed money.
</P>
<P>
The BEA called on colleges and universities to offer students
more work-for-study activities on their campuses. About 8,000
students now participate in work-for-study programs in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Poor students often have difficulty paying for meals and
tuition, said Liu Qiang, a BEA official responsible for the
affairs of college students.
</P>
<P>
Some students can't qualify for scholarship funds because of
their poor academic records. They don't apply for loans because
they are not sure if they can pay off the loans. And they don't
participate in the work-for-study program because they are afraid
their classwork will suffer, he said.
</P>
<P>
The BEA conducted a survey of poor college and university
students in Beijing last year. The survey found that 13,000
students, more than ten percent of the capital's college student
population, were living on less than 14 US dollars a month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
