<HEADLINE> Quality Counts in Drive to Promote Rural Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- An experiment to raise the
standard and quality of production in China's vast rural areas has
been hailed as a success, according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
After just a year, the pilot program at factories in 52 of the
country's county areas has led to higher quality standards and a
more economic use of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
The successes have helped to promote local economies. And it
has emphasized the urgent need for a system of standardizing
quality and production methods in rural industries.
</P>
<P>
"We first introduced the experiment in the counties on a
voluntary basis in April 1995, aiming to examine the experience of
coping with the problem of production being operated without any
proper definite standards. The experiment also promoted technical
progress in factories in the counties," said Yuan Huanan, an
official at the State Bureau of Technical Supervision.
</P>
<P>
The experiment in a second group of another 50 counties,
selected last year, is nearing an end, Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
County economies are becoming an important part of the national
economy, with the total output value of county industries reaching
44 percent of the country's total industrial output value in 1995,
official statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rapid development, county economies face such
dilemmas as a weak technical basis and poor management. These
factors have led to substandard products, a waste of natural
resources and a weak competition.
</P>
<P>
Before 1995, an average one-third of the industrial products in
the 52 counties were produced without any definite technical
standards every year, according to the findings of investigations
into more than 57,000 kinds of products produced by nearly 5,000
factories.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
