<HEADLINE> Illegal Villas to Be Pulled down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Nine two-storey villas, erected in
a protected zone meant to preserve an ancient city wall, will be
torn down within a month, today's China daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The developers face further punishment for starting
construction of the villas in Beijing's Haidian District without
government approval and for damaging cultural relics, according to
Beijing Administrative Bureau of Cultural Relics.
</P>
<P>
Part of the area in which relics were found was ripped up when
foundations for the villas were laid.
</P>
<P>
The illegal construction occupies 1,000 square meters of the
protected zone, according to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The zone runs along the 12-kilometer city wall, which was put
up during the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368). The zone was created in
1984 and was preserved for parkland.
</P>
<P>
The remaining northern and western sections of the old wall
were among the first ancient artifacts to be nominated as city
cultural relics in 1957.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the villas began at the end of 1996. Local
authorities halted the work in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
