<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (9-10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (9-10) in
a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What is "a high degree of autonomy?" What autonomous
powers does the Hong Kong SAR enjoy?
</P>
<P>
Answer: "A high degree of autonomy" means the full enjoyment
of powers to independently administer local affairs. The
autonomous powers of the Hong Kong SAR have the following features:
</P>
<P>
First, non-interference. The central authorities will not
interfere in affairs within the autonomous power of the Hong Kong
SAR.
</P>
<P>
Second, finality of decision making. The Hong Kong SAR will
have final power over matters within its autonomous power as
prescribed in the Basic Law. No approval from the central
authorities is necessary.
</P>
<P>
And third, the right to choose executive means for the exercise
of such power. The government of the Hong Kong SAR may, within
limits as prescribed by the Basic Law, independently choose
executive means for the exercise of its autonomous powers.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, the autonomous power of the Hong
Kong SAR refers mainly to executive, legislative and independent
judicial powers, including the power of final adjudication.
</P>
<P>
With respect to the executive power, the Basic Law, aside from
authorizing the Hong Kong SAR to handle its own administrative
affairs, gives the Hong Kong SAR autonomy in finance, economy,
industry, commerce, trade, transport, development and management
of land and natural resources, education, science and technology,
culture, sports, public order and entry and exit controls.
</P>
<P>
Most notably, the law stipulates that Hong Kong have
independent finances, that its revenues be not handed over to the
central government, that the central authorities levy no taxes in
the region, that Hong Kong may formulate monetary and financial
policies on its own, that the Hong Kong dollar remain to be the
legal tender in the region, and that the authority to issue Hong
Kong currency be vested in the government of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
With respect to legislative power, the Basic Law stipulates
that the Hong Kong SAR may, on its own, enact laws without
violating the Basic Law and continue to enforce previous laws that
do not contravene the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Laws enacted by the SAR should be reported to the National
People's Congress Standing Committee for the record. Only when it
considers that a law enacted by the SAR legislature is incongruent
with the Basic Law, will the NPC Standing Committee reject the law
in question; the Standing Committee will not amend it.
</P>
<P>
Rejection by the NPC Standing Committee means the law's
immediate invalidation. Such invalidation will have no
retroactive power.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong SAR also has independent judicial power,
including that of final adjudication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CEPAL Advocates Economic Growth With Justice To Erradicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Economic Commission for
Latin America and the Caribbean (CEPAL, its acronym in Spanish)
fought today for economic growth with justice to erradicate
poverty in the region.
</P>
<P>
In absolute terms, the number of Latin Americans and Caribbeans
living in poverty, totalling 210 million, is the highest ever,
pointed out the Cepal in a report entitled "The Distribution Gap,
Latin America and the Caribbean and the Social Summit".
</P>
<P>
"Growth itself does not guarantee better distributional
effects," pointed out the Santiago-based organization which is
affiliated to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Cepal disseminated the study to facilitate the debates of
the first regional follow-up conference of the World Summit on
Social Development being held this year in Sao Paulo, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The magnitude of economic growth and the reduction of inflation
is the first determining factor for reducing poverty; the second
is a persistent effort to increase social spending and, more
recently, assigning it more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
The organization said that, on the average, poverty decreased
from 41 to 39 percent in Latin America during the first 5-year
period of the 90s and that this progress is insufficient to offset
the increase in the last decade (from 35 to 41 percent). (to be
continued)
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
