<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Repairs on Second Ring Road to Complete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyclists and drivers will have
smoother rides on Beijing's bumpy second ring road from next
month, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Road repairs which began on March 18 are scheduled to be
completed by then.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 vehicles an hour use the second ring road.
</P>
<P>
This is far more than that the road was designed to accommodate
when it was constructed in the 1970's, according to a spokesperson
at the Beijing Municipal Engineering Administration.
</P>
<P>
Winter's icy temperatures and summer's abundant rains are
responsible for deep cracks in the road which has been heavily
utilized for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
A lack of funds for road repairs led to the second ring road
remaining untended for a long time, the source said.
</P>
<P>
The more than six million yuan (722,000 US dollars) repair
project is the biggest since the road was built.
</P>
<P>
To avoid interruption of normal traffic on this major artery in
the capital, the workers begin their work at nine pm and end at
four or five am the next morning.
</P>
<P>
"We ask the workers to try to avoid making noise that would
affect the residents' lives and to clear away refuse before
leaving," said Xie Shimao, director of the third construction
brigade.
</P>
<P>
Under supervision of construction brigade leaders at the site,
about 30 workers can repair an area 80-90 meters long and 60 wide
in one night.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
