<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Discover Antarctic Ecosystem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have discovered
a large ecosystem on Antarctica's snow-capped land while studying
environmental evolution since the late Pleistocence (about
2,500,000 to 10,000 years ago), a span that included the great ice
age.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) obtained,
by means of drilling, a 701.62-meter-long ice core and a
64.3-meter-long lake core.
</P>
<P>
They found that nutritive elements in the lake core were such
that it was possible to start an ecological chain.
</P>
<P>
This led them to conclude that there was a large ecosystem on
the Antarctic snowmass, following studies on the Antarctic
shoreline and in the southern ocean.
</P>
<P>
They also got a clearer picture of the distribution of krill in
the area, leading to Chinese development and use of krill.
</P>
<P>
China started its research on Antarctica in 1980. The first
Chinese Antarctic research station, Changcheng Station, was built
in 1985, followed by the Zhongshan Station, four years later.
</P>
<P>
China has sent 13 groups of researchers to Antarctica over the
past 12 years. Research on the role that Antarctica has played in
global climate changes is the focus of Chinese scientists for the
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
