<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Breakthrough in Detecting Coal Spontaneous Combustion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- China has made an important
discovery in monitoring the spontaneous combustion in coal fields,
research on which has possible international use.
</P>
<P>
Spontaneous combustion in coal mines causes vast waste of coal
resources and severe damage to the environment and miners' lives.
</P>
<P>
For many years, major coal-producing countries of Russia, the
United States, Mongolia and India have put a great deal of capital
and manpower into trying to find a solution, but with little
progress in developing a complete monitoring system.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has paid close attention to the solution
to the problem in coalfields. In 1993, together with the ITC
Research Institute of the Netherlands, the State Science and
Technology Commission and the Ministry of the Coal Industry
launched an international cooperative project for monitoring
spontaneous combustion in coalfields in north China.
</P>
<P>
The joint research project has made great headway, developing
monitoring systems in the northwest, north and northeast parts of
China, and in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region. It has also
developed models for measuring dangerous coal gas levels and for
policy-making for investment in key projects.
</P>
<P>
The official source said that research findings have drawn
international attention, and that India has invited China to help
it solve problems in its spontaneous combustion monitoring in
coalfields.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
