<HEADLINE> Shanghai Looking at Wild Animal Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- China's largest commercial center
plans to survey its wildlife resources in two years, to find
better means of protection, according to a local source.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has a large proportion of the country's species of
wild animals, with 40 species of mammals, 429 species of birds, 14
species of amphibious animals, and 32 species of reptiles,
including 58 that are under special state protection.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Wild Animal Zoo alone has 5,000 animals of nearly
130 species. The zoo has succeeded in breeding 50 animals from 16
species in recent years, including 5 tigers and 14 African lions.
</P>
<P>
The source said that Shanghai surveys wild animals every ten
years, paying close attention to distribution, number, and the ecology
related to wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has set up a special investigative team that has invited
many experts as advisers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
