<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says to Have Frank Talks with Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Monday that he had a "specific, frank, candid and long
talks" with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over the
Middle East peace process, which, because of Israel's violation of
Israeli-Palestinians peace agreements, has gone aground.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton declined to provide details of their discussions,
only saying: "We'll do our very best" to pull the peace process
back on track.
</P>
<P>
Before his meeting with Netanyahu at the White House, Clinton
made some remarks, obviously biased for Israel, that Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat should first denounce terrorism as a
precondition for peace negotiations between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"Under any sense of human rights and human decency, we ought to
have zero tolerance for terrorism," Clinton told reporters at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
Violent clashes have continued for more than two weeks since
Israeli bulldozers broke ground in traditionally Arab east
Jerusalem, and outraged Palestinians, out on streets in strong
protests, were confronted with Israeli soldiers coming for
suppression.
</P>
<P>
Israel's violation of the peace agreements were greeted with
world-wide condemnation and U.N. Security Council had twice made
resolutions demanding Israel to relinquish its decision to build
6,500 homes for Jews in east Jerusalem, but was twice vetoed by
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, once made a gesture for peace by criticizing Israel's
housing project as not helpful for building confidence between the
two sides, this time concentrated his pressure, not on Netanyahu,
but on Palestinian leader Arafat, saying "zero tolerance" was a
precondition for resuming the suspended peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"I think the important thing is to create the environment in
which the steps can be taken which will make peace possible. And
one precondition of that, obviously, is the absence of terrorism,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also indicated he was not prepared to set up a
David-camp-like summit meeting between Netanyahu and Arafat under
U.S. auspices.
</P>
<P>
"It's important not to jump the gun on that," he said. "The
first thing we have to do is get the process going again. There is
a preexisting process. There are a whole lot of agreements."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, knowing the United States would stand by Israel when
he brandishes an anti-terrorism wand while deliberately
obliterating the real cause of violent clashes on the West Bank.
ceded not an inch from his government's decision to build the
Jewish neighborhood in Arab east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Before his talks with Clinton on Monday, he declared that 75
percent of the land in which Jewish homes were under construction
in east Jerusalem was owned by Jews.
</P>
<P>
"What's wrong with this?" he said at a Jews' gathering in
Washington. "Nothing. People get married, have kids, build homes."
</P>
<P>
Arafat had demanded the housing construction be halted before
preace talks are resumed. But Netanyahu refused, saying: "We are
not going to do this."
</P>
<P>
Following Netanyahu's talks with Clinton, a Palestinian
delegation is due in Washington later this week for talks on the
impasse in the Middle East negotiations.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that there
might be some new ideas and hard work for resumption of the peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"It is a moment in which the peace process needs new ideas and
hard work and the president is prepared to deliver," he told
reporters at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said in New Delhi
that it was "quite possible" the General Assembly would convene in
special session on the Middle East issue in response to an appeal
by Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
