<DOCNO> XIE19970408.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Surges to 51-Month High Against Japanese Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar surpassed 125
Japanese yen for the first time in more than four years Monday and
surged against the mark.
</P>
<P>
The higher U.S. interest rates and optimism over Europe's
single-currency plan played a major role in dollar's surge.
</P>
<P>
The dollar closed in New York at 125.56 yen, up from 124.31 yen
Friday, almost strongest since mid-January 1993. The dollar is up
8.31 percent against the yen this year and up 57 percent since
reaching a postwar low of just under 80 yen two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Against the mark the dollar rose to 1.7109 marks, up 1.5
percent from 1.6854 Friday and the highest level in a month. The
pound cost 1.6295 U.S. dollars, down from 1.6355 U.S. dollars. The
dollar rose sharply in most other dealings.
</P>
<P>
And rebounding U.S. stock prices also contributed to the
strength in the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
Further dollar buying was spurred by Bundesbank President Hans
Tietmeyer of Germany, who suggested that G-7 central banks aren't
terribly worried about the U.S. currency's latest hikes and
weren't likely to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Expectations that Japan's low rates won't rise soon further
attracted Japanese investors.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Friday: 1.4674
Swiss francs, up from 1.4427; 5.7530 French francs, up from 5.6740;
1,684.00 Italian lira, up from 1,667.20; 1.3867 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.3920.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
