<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First NPT Preparatory Committee Begins Two-week Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The first nuclear
Non-proliferation Treaty (NPT) Preparatory Committee (Prepcom)
since the Treaty's indefinite extension in 1995 began on Monday a
two-week session.
</P>
<P>
As part of the package of agreements that led to indefinite
extension, PrepComs have a new substantive role, focusing on ways
to implement the NPT and the Principles and Objectives for Nuclear
Non-Proliferation and Disarmament agreed at the 1995 NPT Review
and Extension Conference.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, there will be three preparatory committee
meetings respectively in 1997, 1998 and 1999 to be followed by a
Review Conference in 2000.
</P>
<P>
In the 1995 NPT Review and Extension Conference, the
nuclear-weapon states also pledged to pursue in a determined
manner systematic and progressive efforts to reduce nuclear
weapons globally, with the ultimate goal of eliminating those
weapons.
</P>
<P>
But while Non-aligned countries insist on reviewing both the
procedural and substantial issues, the West favor only procedural
ones. The Non-allinged countries hope that the PrepCom can become
"mini-Review Conference", but the West refused, arguing that would
pre-empt the outcome the Review Conference.
</P>
<P>
A lot of Non-governmental organizations have also come to the
meeting and urged PrepCom to take up substantial matters and use
the opportunity to push nuclear disarmament foreword.
</P>
<P>
"The first PreCom will determine the future of the
non-proliferation regime," said Dan Plesch of the British American
Security Information Council. "It must make progress on issues of
substance."
</P>
<P>
"If the PrepCom is forced to deal primarily with procedural
issue, this will undermine the 1995 agreements," he warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
