<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Debt Up 6.7 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The consumer credit in the U.S.
increased at annual rate of 6.7 percent in February following a
sharp gain in January, the U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed said that consumer debt rose to 1.21 trillion
dollars after an increase at a 10.3 percent rate in January, the
largest since last July.
</P>
<P>
The gain in January was revised up from an earlier 8.4 percent
estimate announced one month ago.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending in the U.S. represents about two-thirds of
overall activity in the country. Borrowing by consumers has grown
every month since May 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Fed report said that much of the increased borrowing is
coming in credit card debt, which grew at a 12.7 percent annual
rate in February after surging higher at a 21.6 rate in January,
the biggest gain in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
However, automobile borrowing slowed to a rate of 0.3 percent
rate after rising at a 3.1 percent rate in January.
</P>
<P>
Other kinds of consumer debt, including loans for mobile homes,
education, boats and vacations, rose at a 5.5 percent rate in
February following an advance at a 2.9 percent rate the month
before.
</P>
<P>
The latest report fits with other evidence suggesting that the
U.S. economic growth in the first quarter continued at around the
same pace of the fourth quarter. The U.S. economy expanded at a
rate of 3.8 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe Americans' borrowing binge will begin to
slow this year.
</P>
<P>
They expect the Fed, which nudged short-term interest rates up
by a quarter of a percentage point late last month, to continue to
increase the cost of borrowing in an effort to slow economic
growth and prevent inflationary imbalances from developing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
