<HEADLINE> US Pledges no GIs Despite Continuing Unrest in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States will not
deploy troops in Albania, the State Department said today,
expressing concern about the continued unrest in the Balkan
country.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is greatly concerned about the continued
unrest and political polarization in Albania," said Nicholas
Burns, the State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim Fino's convoy was attacked on
Saturday on its way to addressing a group and political tensions
are still rising in the country.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 people have reportedly been killed and hundreds were
hurt while more than 13,000 people fled to Italy from the country
since the chaos started in Albania.
</P>
<P>
"We call on all Albanians and all groups in Albania not to
interfere in the process of reintegration and stabilization, and
to pursue their concerns through dialogue," Burns stressed.
</P>
<P>
"It is the responsibility of all Albanians to ensure the
success of the government of national reconciliation, which was
formed with the agreement of all major Albanian political
parties," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman affirmed that the Albanian government enjoys
"broad international support."
</P>
<P>
"The United States remains committed to working with this
government -- as do, of course, all of the other countries that
are working in Albania," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
However, he declared that the U.S. will not plan to deploy any
forces in the troubled country, saying that it supports the
efforts of Turkey, Greece and Italy to try to stabilize the
situation.
</P>
<P>
An international peacekeeping force of 5,000 to 6,000 troops,
which was approved by the United Nations and formed by France,
Greece, Turkey and other European countries, will be sent to
Albania on April 14. The force is led by Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
