<HEADLINE> Britain Unlikely to Join EMU in First Wave: Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain's main opposition Labor
leader Tony Blair has indicated that a Labor government would keep
open Britain's option on joining the European Monetary Union
(EMU), but it was highly unlikely that Britain would join in the
first wave.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview on BBC television this evening, Blair
said: "The option remains open. But it is highly unlikely we'll be
in the first wave and that then reduced the probability that you
would enter in the next parliament."
</P>
<P>
Blair, whose party is tipped to win a landslide victory in the
coming general election, stressed that it was important that
Britain should remained engaged in the European Union (EU)
negotiations because it would be affected whether it stayed in or
out if EU partners moved to closer European integration.
</P>
<P>
The Labor party, which maintained a pro-European stance, has
recently hardened its position on Britain's membership in the EMU,
by effectively ruling out joining the single currency within the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
Labor's shadow foreign secretary Robin Cook was reported as
saying on Sunday: "If you didn't join (single currency) in 1999,
it's very difficult to see a government that has taken the
decision that Britain wasn't ready in 1999, coming to the decision
it would be ready by the year after or the year after that."
</P>
<P>
"In the event of that Britain doesn't join in the first wave, I
would have thought the probability is that one is looking towards
the subsequent parliament," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
